cre\n|1967\u20131969\n|[[Yangjiang, Guangdong]]\n|3,573<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.yhcqw.com/30/9666.html|title=\u9633\u6c5f\"\u4e71\u6253\u4e71\u6740\u4e8b\u4ef6\"\u59cb\u672b|last=Chen|first=Baode|last2=Li|first2=Xuechao|date=|website=www.yhcqw.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n|Mainly in [[Yangjiang]] and [[Yangchun]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n|-\n|[[Daoxian massacre]]\n|August \u2013 October\n1967\n|[[Daoxian]], [[Hunan]]\n|9,093<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Tan|first=Hecheng|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0QCDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=daoxian+massacre+7696#v=onepage|title=The Killing Wind: A Chinese County's Descent Into Madness During the Cultural Revolution|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-062252-7|language=en}}</ref>\n|Took place in more than 10 counties, mainly in [[Dao County]].\n|-\n|[[Shaoyang County Massacre]]\n|July \u2013 September \n1968\n|[[Shaoyang County|Shaoyang,]]\n[[Shaoyang County|Hunan]]\n|991<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.modernchinastudies.org/us/issues/past-issues/105-mcs-2009-issue-3/1104-2012-01-05-15-35-41.html|title=\"\u6587\u9769\"\u65f6\u671f\u6e56\u5357\u7701\u90b5\u9633\u53bf\"\u9ed1\u6740\u98ce\"\u4e8b\u4ef6\u59cb\u672b|last=Lin|first=Qishan|date=|work=Modern China Studies|publisher=|language=zh|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|Influenced by Daoxian Massacre.\n|-\n|Dan County Massacre\n|August 1968\n|[[Danzhou, Hainan]]\n|>700<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=Lin|first=Xue|url=https://books.google.com/?id=__e2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA284&dq=%E6%B5%B7%E5%8D%97%E6%96%87%E9%9D%A9%E5%A4%A7%E5%B1%A0%E6%9D%80#v=onepage|title=\u8d75\u7d2b\u9633 \u00b7 \u4ece\u9769\u547d\u5230\u6539\u826f \uff08\u5e7f\u4e1c\u7bc7\uff09|date=2019-10-17|publisher=\u4e16\u754c\u534e\u8bed\u51fa\u7248\u793e|isbn=978-1-940266-62-6|location=|pages