|first=Xue|url=https://books.google.com/?id=__e2DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA284&dq=%E6%B5%B7%E5%8D%97%E6%96%87%E9%9D%A9%E5%A4%A7%E5%B1%A0%E6%9D%80#v=onepage|title=\u8d75\u7d2b\u9633 \u00b7 \u4ece\u9769\u547d\u5230\u6539\u826f \uff08\u5e7f\u4e1c\u7bc7\uff09|date=2019-10-17|publisher=\u4e16\u754c\u534e\u8bed\u51fa\u7248\u793e|isbn=978-1-940266-62-6|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref>\n|Over 50 thousand people were jailed and thousands were permanently disabled. Conducted by People's Liberation Army and local [[Militia|militias]].<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":9\" />\n|-\n|Ruijin Massacre\n|September  \u2013October 1968\n|[[Ruijin, Jiangxi]]\n|>1000<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Yang|first=Jishen|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4d4qDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT515&dq=%E6%B1%9F%E8%A5%BF%E7%91%9E%E9%87%91%E5%A4%A7%E5%B1%A0%E6%9D%80#v=onepage|title=\u5929\u5730\u7ffb\u8986: \u4e2d\u56fd\u6587\u5316\u5927\u9769\u547d\u5386\u53f2|date=2017-07-04|publisher=\u5929\u5730\u56fe\u4e66|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=zh}}</ref>\n|Took place in [[Ruijin|Ruijin County]], [[Xingguo County]], and [[Yudu County]].<ref name=\":7\" />\n|-\n|[[Zhao Jianmin Spy Case]]\n|1968\u20131969\n|[[Yunnan]]\n|17,000<ref name=\":2\" />\n|Over 1.3 million people persecuted. \n|-\n|[[Shadian incident|Shadian Incident]]\n|July \u2013 August\n1975\n|Yunnan\n|1,600<ref>{{Cite book|last=Zhou|first=Yongming|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8Rv-MsA4UGIC&pg=PA162&lpg=PA162&dq=shadian+incident#v=onepage|title=Anti-drug Crusades in Twentieth-century China: Nationalism, History, and State Building|date=1999|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-8476-9598-0|language=en}}</ref>\n|Mostly [[Hui people]]. Conducted by People's Liberation Army.\n|}\n\n=== 1976\u20131999 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]]\n|1989, June 4\n|[[Tiananmen Square]], Beijing\n|{{ntsh|241}}200-10,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-42465516|title=Tiananmen Square death toll 'was 10,000'|date=2017-12-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-06-02/tiananmen-square-massacre-30-year-anniversary/11163332|title='Consternation, fear and disbelief': Chinese soldier remembers Tiananmen Square massacre|last=Xiao|first=Bang|date=2019-06-02|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n|Between 200 and 10,000 civilians were killed. [[International Committee of the Red Cross|The Red Cross]] states that around 2,600 died and the official Chinese government figure is 241 dead with 7,000 wounded.{{sfn|Zhang|2001|p=436}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/notesandqueries/query/0,5753,-2317,00.html|title=The \"Tiananmen Square massacre\" is constantly referred to. Why have I never seen film or video footage of a single death? The cameras were there, were they not? {{!}} Notes and Queries {{!}} guardian.co.uk|website=www.theguardian.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]]'s estimates puts the number of deaths at several hundred to close to 1,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/download/Documents/200000/asa170091990en.pdf|title=The massacre of June 1989 and its aftermath|last=|first=|date=|website=Amnesty International|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[NATO]] intelligence reported around 7,000 and the [[Soviet Union]] reported around 10,000.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} As many as 10,000 estimated people were arrested during the protests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/15/world/asia/tiananmen-square-fast-facts/index.html|title=Tiananmen Square Fast Facts|last=Library|first=C. N. N.|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Thousand Island Lake incident|Thousand Island Lake robbery killings]]\n|1994, March 31\n|[[Zhejiang Province]]\n|{{ntsh|32}}32\n|24 Taiwanese tourists, 6 crew members, and 2 mainland Chinese passengers on board the \"Hai Rui\" sightseeing cruise were robbed and murdered. The incident cast a shadow over cross-strait relations.<ref>[http://news.hexun.com/2008-04-25/105559139.html \u7b2c67\u671f\uff1a\u5343\u5c9b\u6e56\u4e8b\u4ef6(\u7ec4\u56fe), (April 25, 2008)]</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ghulja Incident]]\n|1997, February 5\n|[[Ghulja]], [[Xinjiang]]\n|{{ntsh|9}}9\n|Demonstrations in Ghulja were violently put down by police after two days of protesting. Official reports put the death toll at 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/50936.stm|title=China Uighurs executed|date=1998-01-27|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|Long wins round robbery\n|1998 November 15\n|[[Shanwei]]\n|{{ntsh|23}}23\n|Guangdong Province, Shanwei City, the territory of an armed robbery case, the Hong Kong shipping company \"Changsheng\" million tons of cargo ship on which 23 Chinese expatriate crew were all killed and their corpses dumped into the sea.<ref>[http://news.sohu.com/00/52/news201825200.shtml \u957f\u80dc\u8f6e23\u4eba\u60e8\u6848\u4e00\u4e3b\u72af\u843d\u7f51 \u5927\u6d77\u76d7\u5f20\u519b\u7ea2\u5373\u5c06\u53d7\u5ba1, (June 24, 2002)]</ref>\n|}\n\n=== 2000\u2013 ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!Name\n!Date\n!Location\n!Deaths\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[2014 Kunming attack|Kunming massacre]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/10675219/Kunming-massacre-Has-the-global-jihad-reached-China.html|title=Kunming massacre: Has the global jihad reached China?|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref>\n|2014, March 1\n|[[Kunming]]\n|{{ntsh|33}}33 (including four perpetrators)\n|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Mass killings under communist regimes]]\n* [[Great Chinese Famine|Great Chinese famine]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-mass-killings-during-chinese-cultural-revolution-1966-1976 \"Chronology of Mass Killings during the Chinese Cultural Revolution (1966-1976)\"] by Song Yongyi\n\n{{Massacres}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of massacres by country|China]]\n[[Category:China history-related lists|Massacres]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of disasters in China]]\n", "name_user": "SCreditC", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1966\u20131976 (Cultural Revolution)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_massacres_in_China"}
{"title_page": "Kulturpalast (Dresden)", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Kulturpalast gesehen vom Altmarkt.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast Dresden, view from Altmarkt/Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe (2006)]]\nThe '''Kulturpalast Dresden''' is a [[Modern architecture|modernist]] [[East Germany|GDR]]-era building built by the architect Wolfgang H\u00e4nsch. It opened in 1969 and had the largest multi-purpose hall in the city of [[Dresden]] [[Germany]]. The hall was used for concerts, dance and entertainment events, as well as conferences and congresses. After several years of reconstruction, including the installation of a new concert hall, it reopened in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=J\u00fcrgen Tietz|url=https://www.nzz.ch/feuilleton/dresdens-neuer-konzertsaal-spaete-harmonien-ld.1289905|title=Sp\u00e4te Harmonien {{!}} NZZ|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung|access-date=2020-03-14|language=de}}</ref>\n\nThe building is, however, not in the unadorned [[International Style (architecture)|international style]] unlike the other buildings on the \"Altmarkt\" square. It is a stand-alone building with a floor area of around 700 meters squared. It forms the second part of the \"Altmarkt\" square and faces Wilsdruffer Strasse.  Located east of Schlo\u00dfstra\u00dfe and southwest of nearby [[Neumarkt (Dresden)|Neumarkt,]] which has been undergoing a reconstruction project since 2005, it lies in the centre of the historic old town, which was largely destroyed during the [[firebombing of Dresden]] on 13 February 1945. \n\n== History ==\n[[File:19670211 Baustelle Kulturpalast, Frauenkirche.jpg|thumb|Foundations of the Kulturpalast (1967)]]\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1985-0918-026, Dresden, Kulturpalast.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast (1985)]]\nOriginally, the Kulturpalast was planned as a socialist-classicist ensemble building. After further planning, the intention was to erect a high-rise building in the style of the [[Seven Sisters (Moscow)|seven Moscow sister high-rise buildings]]. Following the \"[[The Sixteen Principles of Urban Design|16 Principles of Urban Development\"]] and the GDR's construction law in 1950, the principles of socialist urban development were then to be implemented in the GDR. Important principles were: a central square, cityscape-forming high-rise buildings and wide main roads. The Kulturpalast was originally intended to take over this function of the dominant high ground. However, the project was not realized in the 1950s.\n\nThe Kulturpalast was released in the 1960s as the cultural centre of the city and [[Bezirk Dresden|district of Dresden]]. It was also known as a cuboid building with an eaves of 19.35 m, based on the architectural planning of Leopold Wiel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kulturpalast-dresden-erhalten.de/|title=Index@www.Kulturpalast-Dresden-Erhalten.de|website=www.kulturpalast-dresden-erhalten.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Initially, there was a planned third floor and a grandstand for the parades on [[Ernst-Th\u00e4lmann-Stra\u00dfe]] but they were never built.\n\n=== Fire protection refurbishment 2007 ===\nDue to improperly carried out reconstruction work in the 1990s, it became necessary to renovate the Kulturpalast's fire protection equipment, which required a five-month closure from 19 March 2007. In the weeks before the renovation work began, fire engines were positioned directly next to the Palace of Culture during events.\n\n=== Last years before the renovation ===\nSince 2008, the Kulturpalast has been a listed building. The \"Palast\", colloquially known as ''Kulti'', it fulfils the functions of a town hall and has an important function in the cultural life of the city. It is operated by the ''Konzert- und Kongressgesellschaft mbH Dresden''. The main user is the [[Dresden Philharmonic|Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\nEvery year it served as the main venue for the [[Internationales Dixieland Festival Dresden|Dixieland Festival]]. In 2011, it was used as an organization centre, main information and venue for the [[German Evangelical Church Assembly]].\n\nOn July 23, 2012, ''Das Br\u00fcckenm\u00e4nnchen l\u00e4dt ein \u2013 Der kleine Vampir'' (The Bridge Manikin Invites - The Little Vampire) was the last performance before the reconstruction of the Palace of Culture. Afterwards the house was closed and completely cleared out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnn.de|title=Letzte Vorstellung im Dresdner Kulturpalast \u2013 Proteste gegen Umbau halten an.|last=|first=|date=2012-07-23|website=|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref>\n\n== Building ==\n[[File:Weg der Roten Fahne.jpg|thumb|Wall painting ''Der Weg der [[Red flag (politics)|roten Fahne]]'' (The way of the red flag)]]\n\n=== Until 2012 ===\nBefore 2012, the multi-functional ballroom with up to 2435 seats (formerly 2740) could be transformed into an auditorium completely furnished with fixed rows of seats and elevation or into a banquet hall with a flat floor in the area of the parquet in front of the stage thanks to the special \"tilting parquet\".\n\nThe banquet hall was optimized for multi-functionality in its room acoustics and had been adapted for use as a concert hall or for electronically amplified music or speech events through variable absorption or reflection surfaces.\n\nIn addition to the large hall, the Kulturpalast had a studio theatre with 192 seats, seminar, rehearsal and performance rooms, foyer levels, office wings and a restaurant with conference facilities.\n\nOutwardly, the ballroom is distinguished by the roof, which protrudes from the cuboid base structure and has the base area of a symmetrical trapezoid.\n\n=== Wall Painting ===\n[[File:Der Weg der roten Fahne-Inschriften.jpg|thumb|Inscriptions on the wall painting]]\nThe 30 meter by 10.5 meter mural ''Der Weg der [[Red flag (politics)|Roten Fahne]]'' (The way of the red flag) on the west side of the building has been designated a cultural monument since 2001. In 1968 Gerhard Bondzin was commissioned to develop the designs. The mural was realized until 1969 by a working group of the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]]. The working title was: \u201e1849 - 1969: 120 Jahre Kampf der revolution\u00e4ren Kr\u00e4fte der Stadt f\u00fcr Fortschritt und Sozialismus\u201c (1849 - 1969: 120 years of struggle of the revolutionary forces of the city for progress and socialism).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saechsische.de/der-weg-der-roten-fahne-haelt-fuer-die-ewigkeit-2658892.html|title=\"Der Weg der roten Fahne\" h\u00e4lt f\u00fcr die Ewigkeit|website=www.saechsische.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In addition to Bondzin (artistic director), the artists' collective included Alfred Hesse (participation in transmission work), Gerhard Stengel (artistic technology), Gerhard Pr\u00e4kelt (architect), Emil Spiess (study organization), Martin H\u00e4nisch (type design), Wolfgang Richter (specialist instructor) and students in the 3rd and 4th year of the mural design course. It consists of colored glass on concrete slabs that have been electrostatically coated - a technique that was used for the first time in a mural of this size.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kober|first=Rudolf|title=Wandbilder in der Deutschen Demokratischen Republik|publisher=|year=1987|isbn=|volume=5|location=Berlin, Germany|pages=24\u201333, 39|language=german}}</ref>\nThe text in the mural reads: ''\u201eDie Befreiung der Arbeiterklasse kann nur das Werk der Arbeiterklasse selbst sein. Leben wird unser Programm. Trotz alledem wir sind der Sieger der Geschichte! Gewidmet dem 20. Jahrestag der DDR. Entstanden in sozialistischer Gemeinschaftsarbeit der Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Dresden\u201c (''The liberation of the working class can only be the work of the working class itself. Life becomes our program. Despite all this, we are the victor of history! Dedicated to the 20th anniversary of the GDR. Created in socialist community work of the Dresden Academy of Fine Arts)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Der_Weg_der_Roten_Fahne|title=Category:Der Weg der Roten Fahne|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe wall frieze Unser sozialistisches Leben by Heinz Drache and Walter Rehn measuring 45 meters \u00d7 1.90 meters on the first floor was preserved during the renovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kulturpalast-dresden.de/de/foyers.html|title=Foyers - Kulturpalast Dresden|website=www.kulturpalast-dresden.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Doors ===\n[[File:+Kulturpalast Dresden - Eingangst\u00fcre - (DDR) - Bild 004.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast Dresden: Entrance door after reconstruction]]\nThe five bronze main entrance doors were created by [[Gerd Jaeger]] in 1969 and represent Dresden's development from a fishing village to a large city. The bronze casting of the doors was carried out by the foundry Pirner & Franz in Dresden.\n\n=== Well ===\nIn front of the building, there are three [[water feature]]s which were created in 1969 on Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe. The fountains were later removed in the course of the construction work for the underground car park at Altmarkt. These were [[terrazzo]] pools measuring 7.90 by 8.55 metres. In each basin there was a jet fountain on an area of 3 by 3 meters, 24 small heap fountains were installed at the edge of the basin.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Kunst im \u00f6ffentlichen Raum|publisher=Kulturamt Dresden|year=1996|isbn=|location=Dresden, Germany|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\nDresden Altmarkt Sicht auf Kulturpalast 1 Panorama.jpg|Panorama of the Palace of Culture from the Altmarkt (February 2017)\nAltmarkt dresden kulturpalast2.JPG|View over the Altmarkt to the Kulturpalast, behind it the [[Dresden Frauenkirche]], which was rebuilt until 2005 \nAltmarkt (Dresden)2009 06.jpg|Close-up with Frauenkirche and row building at Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe, 2009\n20121008160DR DD Blick v d Frauenkirche Richtung Altmarkt.jpg|View from the Frauenkirche over the reborn Neumarkt, Kulturpalast and Altmarkt, 2012\nDD-Kulturpalast-Foyer.jpg|Foyer of the Kulturpalast\nDD-Kulturpalast-Obergeschoss-1.jpg|First floor with the wall frieze 'Unser sozialistisches Leben' ''Our socialist life''\nDD-Kulturpalast-Bibo-1.jpg|Central Library of the Municipal Libraries\n</gallery>\n\n== Conversion ==\n[[File:DD-Kulturpalast-Saal-04.jpg|thumb|The new concert hall]]\n\n=== Conversion planning ===\n[[File:Dresdner Philharmonie im Kulturpalast 2.jpg|thumb|The Dresden Philharmonic and the organ in the renovated Kulturpalast]]\nIn October 2013 the reconstruction work on the Palace of Culture began.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresden.de/de/rathaus/aktuelles/pressemitteilungen/archiv/2013/10/pm_050.php|title=Baustart im Dresdner Kulturpalast|last=Dresden|website=www.dresden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The festival hall was to be converted into a pure concert hall with a reduced capacity as a venue for the Dresden Philharmonic. The studio stage, seminar rooms and other used areas of the Kulturpalast were to be redesigned as the venue for the Herkuleskeule (Leg of Hercules) and the library operations of the Municipal Library. In addition to cost savings, this was intended to achieve an all-day opening and use of the building by different age and interest groups.\n\n=== Architecture competition ===\nTo achieve the conversion, the state capital announced an architectural competition in which the office of [[Gerkan, Marg and Partners|Gerkan, Marg and Partner]] won the first prize unanimously and with a recommendation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresden.de/de/rathaus/aktuelles/pressemitteilungen/archiv/2009/06/pm_110.php|title=Jury ermittelte Siegerentwurf zum Kulturpalastumbau|last=Dresden|website=www.dresden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The design envisaged a pure concert hall in the shape of a [[vineyard]] (similar to the hall of the [[Gewandhaus]] in [[Leipzig]], Germany), which should offer good conditions for the Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra.\n\n=== Reopening 2017 ===\nAfter reconstruction and renovation, the Kulturpalast was reopened on April 28, 2017, with a festive concert by the Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2017-05-03|title=Ein zauberischer Dunst|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/|journal=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|volume=|pages=12|via=}}</ref> The old festival hall was converted into the new concert hall with a reduced capacity of up to 1800 seats. Thus, the Dresden Philharmonic has regained its traditional venue. The new concert hall is also used by international orchestras for concerts. Its acoustics are praised by musicians, audiences and press alike.\n\nIn addition, the Dresden Municipal Libraries (Central Library) and the Dresden cabaret \"Die Herkuleskeuleule\" have now also found their new home here. This means that the building can be opened and used all day long.\n\nThe problem of an adequate multifunctional hall was not addressed or solved in this context but remains open (as of 2017).\n\n== Organ ==\n=== Jehmlich-Organ from 1970 ===\nThe [[Jehmlich Orgelbau Dresden|Jehmlich company]] installed an organ in the Great Hall as Opus 905 in 1970. A pipe organ in a large state cultural institution was still something special at a time when the socialist cultural policy was slow to open up to music with organ parts.\n\nThe instrument had 24 [[Organ stop|stops]] distributed over two [[Manual (music)|manuals]] and [[Pedal keyboard|pedal]]. The disposition corresponding to a universal organ was developed in cooperation with the Dresden organ scientist Prof. Frank-Harald Gre\u00df. The organ with the dimensions (W \u00d7 H \u00d7 D) 7.4 m \u00d7 7.4 m \u00d7 1.5 m stood on a mobile steel frame on which it could be pushed onto the stage on rails specially laid for this purpose. However, this mobility and the shortage of money set clear limits to the size of the organ, which at that time had a very modest capacity for a hall with well over 2000 seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jehmlich-orgelbau.de/orgelprojekte/cottbus-propsteikirche/|title=Cottbus, Kath. Propsteikirche St. Marien, 2 Manuale 24 Register, Gebr. Jehmlich 1970, Restaurierung 2015|last=Jehmlich|first=Evelyn|website=Jehmlich Orgelbau Dresden|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The pipes stood on three slider chests, the [[tracker action]] was mechanical and the stop action electro-pneumatic.\n\nIn the course of the major reconstruction of the concert hall, the organ was dismantled in 2012 and, after an overhaul, rebuilt in 2015 in the Provost and Parish Church of St. Maria Friedensk\u00f6nigin in [[Cottbus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orgbase.nl/scripts/ogb.exe?database=ob2&%250=2026024&LGE=DE&LIJST=lang&OLC=5005164|title=Orgel Databank {{!}} Beschreibung Orgel|website=orgbase.nl|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''I Main plant''' C\u2013f<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''II Swell''' C\u2013f<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Pedal''' C\u2013f<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|1.\n|Pomerania\n|16\u2032\n|10.\n|Pointed viol\n|8\u2032\n|19.\n|Subba\u00df\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|2.\n|Principal\n|8\u2032\n|11.\n|Dacked\n|8\u2032\n|20.\n|Principalba\u00df\n|8\u2032\n|-\n|3.\n|Reed pipe\n|8\u2032\n|12.\n|Principal\n|4\u2032\n|21.\n|Gemshorn\n|4\u2032\n|-\n|4.\n|Octave\n|4\u2032\n|13.\n|Belt flute\n|4\u2032\n|22.\n|Subordinate clause VI\n|\n|-\n|5.\n|Flat flute\n|2\u2032\n|14.\n|Octave\n|2\u2032\n|23.\n|Trombone\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|6.\n|Noise fifth II\n|\n|15.\n|Sifflute\n|1\u2032\n|24.\n|Clarinet\n|4\u2032\n|-\n|7.\n|Mixture VI\n|\n|16.\n|Sesquialtera II\n|\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"4\" |\n|-\n|8.\n|Solo cymbal II\n|\n|17.\n|Sharp\n|\n|-\n|9.\n|Trumpet\n|8\u2032\n|18.\n|Pipe shawl\n|16\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|}\n* Coupling: II/I, I/P, II/P\n* playing aids: 4 free combinations, tutti, reeds off, single reed stop\n\n=== Eule-Organ from 2017 ===\nOn 8 September 2017 the new concert [[Pipe organ|organ]], built by the company Hermann Eule Orgelbau Bautzen, was inaugurated.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresdnerphilharmonie.de/media/content/download/programmhefte/2017_09_08_orgeleinweihung.pdf|title=Einweihung der Konzertorgel|last=|first=|date=2017-09-08|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The financing was largely provided by the Dresden Philharmonic Society of Friends, largely under its chairman George Gerard Arnhold.\n\nThe new instrument has 67 stops (4013 sounding pipes) distributed over four manuals and pedal (slider chest). The main part of the instrument measures 14.7 meters in width, 3.3 meters in depth and 8.5 meters in height, and weighs about 20.5 tons. The action is electric, the [[Organ console|console]] is mobile. A special feature of the instrument is the French horn register, which is placed in a separate sill in the II manual and can be played as a solo register from the IV manual. The registers of the freely connectable bombarde mechanism are located in the sill in the III manual.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''I Main plant''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''II Swell''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''III R\u00e9cit-Orchestral''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''IV Solo'''\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Pedal''' C\u2013g<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|1.\n|Principal\n|16\u2032\n|14.\n|Sweetheart. dacked\n|16\u2032\n|29.\n|Viola\n|16\u2032\n|\n|<u>open</u>\n|\n|50.\n|Grand Bourdon\n|32\u2032\n|-\n|2.\n|Principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|15.\n|Violin principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|30.\n|Principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|44.\n|Melody\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|51.\n|Open Wood\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|3.\n|Large open Diapason\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|16.\n|Salicional\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|31.\n|Viol d'orchestre\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|45.\n|Tuba sonora\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|''52.''\n|''Principal <small>(= Nr. 1)</small>''\n|''16\u2032''\n|-\n|4.\n|Flood major\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|17.\n|Double flute\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|32.\n|Concert Flute\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|\n|<u>swellable</u>\n|\n|53.\n|Violon\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|5.\n|Cello\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|18.\n|Reed pipe\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|33.\n|Tender-headed\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|46.\n|French Horn <small>(=no. 28)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|54.\n|Subbass <small>(Ext. Nr. 50)</small>\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|6.\n|Narrator\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|19.\n|Violin octave\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|34.\n|Aeoline\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Bombarde'''\n|''55.''\n|''Bass dacked <small>(= no. 14)</small>''\n|''16\u2032''\n|-\n|7.\n|Octave\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|20.\n|Flute\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|35.\n|Vox coelestis ''<small>(from G)</small>'' {{0}}\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|47.\n|Bombard\n|16\u2032\n|''56.''\n|''Dulcianabass <small>(= no. 29)</small>'' {{0}}\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|8.\n|Hollow flute\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|21.\n|Nasard\n|{{0}}{{Frac|2|2|3}}\u2032\n|36.\n|Quinta tone\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|48.\n|Trumpet harmonique\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|57.\n|Octavbass\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|9.\n|Fifth\n|{{0}}{{Frac|2|2|3}}\u2032\n|22.\n|Flautino\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|37.\n|Fugara\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|49.\n|Clairon harmonique\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|58.\n|Violoncello <small>(Ext. no. 53)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|10.\n|Octave\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|23.\n|Third\n|{{0}}{{Frac|1|3|5}}\u2032\n|38.\n|Flute octaviante\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"9\" |\n|59.\n|Bass flute <small>(Ext. no. 50)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|11.\n|Mixtur IV\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|24.\n|Progressive III\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|39.\n|Octavin\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|''60.''\n|''Salicetbass <small>(= no. 16)</small>''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|-\n|12.\n|Cornet III\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|25.\n|Cor anglais\n|16\u2032\n|40.\n|Viol-Cornett III\n|{{0}}{{Frac|3|1|5}}\u2032\n|''61.''\n|''Bourdonbass <small>(= no. 30)</small>''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|-\n|13.\n|trumpet\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|26.\n|Cornopean\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|41.\n|Plein jeu V\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|62.\n|Octave <small>(Ext. no. 57)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"5\" |\n|27.\n|Clarinet\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|42.\n|Orchestral Oboe\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|63.\n|Bass flute <small>(Ext. no. 50)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|-\n|''28.''\n|''French Horn (separately swellable)''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|43.\n|Voix Humaine\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|64.\n|Contratrombone\n|32\u2032\n|-\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|65.\n|Trombone <small>(Ext. no. 64)</small>\n|16\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n|66.\n|Bass trombone\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|67.\n|Clairon <small>(Ext. no. 64)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|}\n* Pair up:\n** 10 normal couplings: IV/I, III/I, II/I, III/II, III/I, II/I, I/P, II/P, III/P, IV/P\n** 5 Normal couplers bombarde movement (to all manual movements and the pedal)\n** 5 Sub-octave couplings: III/III, III/I, II/II, II/I, I/I\n** 5 super-octave couplings: III/III, III/I, II/II, II/I, IV/P\n* Game help\n* slider chests, 14 large windchests, 18 single tone chests\n* 10 magazine bellows, 3 pre-bellows, 2 normal pressure and 1 high-pressure fan\n* electric playing and register [[tracker action]] action, BUS system, setting system Eule, MIDI recording function\n* Tuning pitch: 443&nbsp;Hz at 21&nbsp;\u00b0C, type of tuning: equal floating\n* 4,013 sounding pipes, of which 223 pipes from 6 registers in the prospectus (there plus 96 blind pipes).\n* largest pipe: Contra trombone 32\u2032, C, 9.23 m, largest prospect pipe: Principal 16\u2032, 6.73 m<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Literature ==\n* Birk Engmann: ''Bauen f\u00fcr die Ewigkeit: Monumentalarchitektur des zwanzigsten Jahrhunderts und St\u00e4dtebau in Leipzig in den f\u00fcnfziger Jahren.'' Sax-Verlag, Beucha, Germany, 2006, {{ISBN|3-934544-81-9}}, German\n* Wolfgang H\u00e4nsch: ''Haus der sozialistischen Kultur.'' In: ''Deutsche Architektur.'' Issue 4, 1968, P. 212\u2013671, German\n* Meinhard von Gerkan, Stephan Sch\u00fctz (Ed.): ''Kulturpalast Dresden.'' Publisher Jovis Verlag, Berlin 2017, {{ISBN|978-3-86859-484-3}}, German\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Kulturpalast, Dresden|Kulturpalast (Dresden)}}\n* [http://kulturpalast-dresden.de Website Kulturpalast Dresden], German\n* [http://www.das-neue-dresden.de/kulturpalast-dresden.html ''Kulturpalast \u2013 Geistig- kulturelles Zentrum der Stadt und des Bezirkes Dresden.'' ''Palace of Culture - spiritual and cultural centre of the city and district of Dresden.''], German\n* [http://archiv.neumarkt-dresden.de/Kulturpalastareal/dresner-kulturpalast.html Historical facts about the Dresden Palace of Culture] at the website of the Society Historischer Neumarkt Dresden, German\n* [http://www.kulturpalast-dresden-erhalten.de/ Initiative to preserve the Dresden Palace of Culture] (As of 2006), German\n* [http://www.dresden.de/de/kultur/kulturentwicklung/kulturpalast/kulturpalast_chronologie_umbau.php Chronology of the reconstruction] at the website of the city of Dresden, German\n* [http://www.moderne-regional.de/der-dresdner-kulturpalast/ Historical pictures from the construction period], German\n* [http://swb.bsz-bw.de/DB=2.304//CMD?ACT=SRCHA&IKT=8549&TRM=1060085488&COOKIE=Us998,Pbszgast,I2017,B20728+,SY,NRecherche-DB,D2.304,E276107f8-b,A,H,R95.91.215.252,FY S\u00e4chsische Bibliographie], German\n\n{{Coordinate |NS=51/3/3.6/N |EW=13/44/18.6/E |type=landmark |dim=100 |region=DE-SN}}\n\n{{Music venues in Germany}}\n\n[[Category:Concert halls in Germany]]\n[[Category:East German architecture]]\n[[Category:Dresden]]\n[[Category:1960s architecture]]\n[[Category:Organs (music)]]\n[[Category:Individual pipe organs]]\n[[Category:Public venues with a theatre organ]]\n[[Category:Culture of Saxony]]\n[[Category:Entertainment venues in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Kulturpalast gesehen vom Altmarkt.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast Dresden, view from Altmarkt/Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe (2006)]]\nThe '''Kulturpalast Dresden''' is a [[Modern architecture|modernist]] [[East Germany|GDR]]-era building built by the architect Wolfgang H\u00e4nsch. It opened in 1969 and had the largest multi-purpose hall in the city of [[Dresden]] [[Germany]]. The hall was used for concerts, dance and entertainment events, as well as conferences and congresses. After several years of reconstruction, including the installation of a new concert hall, it reopened in April 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|last=J\u00fcrgen Tietz|url=https://www.nzz.ch/feuilleton/dresdens-neuer-konzertsaal-spaete-harmonien-ld.1289905|title=Sp\u00e4te Harmonien {{!}} NZZ|work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung|access-date=2020-03-14|language=de}}</ref>\n\nThe building is, however, not in the unadorned [[International Style (architecture)|international style]] unlike the other buildings on the \"Altmarkt\" square. It is a stand-alone building with a floor area of around 700 meters squared. It forms the second part of the \"Altmarkt\" square and faces Wilsdruffer Strasse.  Located east of Schlo\u00dfstra\u00dfe and southwest of nearby [[Neumarkt (Dresden)|Neumarkt,]] which has been undergoing a reconstruction project since 2005, it lies in the centre of the historic old town, which was largely destroyed during the [[firebombing of Dresden]] on 13 February 1945. \n\n== History ==\n[[File:19670211 Baustelle Kulturpalast, Frauenkirche.jpg|thumb|Foundations of the Kulturpalast (1967)]]\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1985-0918-026, Dresden, Kulturpalast.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast (1985)]]\nOriginally, the Kulturpalast was planned as a socialist-classicist ensemble building. After further planning, the intention was to erect a high-rise building in the style of the [[Seven Sisters (Moscow)|seven Moscow sister high-rise buildings]]. Following the \"[[The Sixteen Principles of Urban Design|16 Principles of Urban Development\"]] and the GDR's construction law in 1950, the principles of socialist urban development were then to be implemented in the GDR. Important principles were: a central square, cityscape-forming high-rise buildings and wide main roads. The Kulturpalast was originally intended to take over this function of the dominant high ground. However, the project was not realized in the 1950s.\n\nThe Kulturpalast was released in the 1960s as the cultural centre of the city and [[Bezirk Dresden|district of Dresden]]. It was also known as a cuboid building with an eaves of 19.35 m, based on the architectural planning of Leopold Wiel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kulturpalast-dresden-erhalten.de/|title=Index@www.Kulturpalast-Dresden-Erhalten.de|website=www.kulturpalast-dresden-erhalten.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> Initially, there was a planned third floor and a grandstand for the parades on [[Ernst-Th\u00e4lmann-Stra\u00dfe]] but they were never built.\n\n=== Fire protection refurbishment 2007 ===\nDue to improperly carried out reconstruction work in the 1990s, it became necessary to renovate the Kulturpalast's fire protection equipment, which required a five-month closure from 19 March 2007. In the weeks before the renovation work began, fire engines were positioned directly next to the Palace of Culture during events.\n\n=== Last years before the renovation ===\nSince 2008, the Kulturpalast has been a listed building. The \"Palast\", colloquially known as ''Kulti'', it fulfils the functions of a town hall and has an important function in the cultural life of the city. It is operated by the ''Konzert- und Kongressgesellschaft mbH Dresden''. The main user is the [[Dresden Philharmonic|Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra]].\n\nEvery year it served as the main venue for the [[Internationales Dixieland Festival Dresden|Dixieland Festival]]. In 2011, it was used as an organization centre, main information and venue for the [[German Evangelical Church Assembly]].\n\nOn July 23, 2012, ''Das Br\u00fcckenm\u00e4nnchen l\u00e4dt ein \u2013 Der kleine Vampir'' (The Bridge Manikin Invites - The Little Vampire) was the last performance before the reconstruction of the Palace of Culture. Afterwards the house was closed and completely cleared out.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnn.de|title=Letzte Vorstellung im Dresdner Kulturpalast \u2013 Proteste gegen Umbau halten an.|last=|first=|date=2012-07-23|website=|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref>\n\n== Building ==\n[[File:Weg der Roten Fahne.jpg|thumb|Wall painting ''Der Weg der [[Red flag (politics)|roten Fahne]]'' (The way of the red flag)]]\n\n=== Until 2012 ===\nBefore 2012, the multi-functional ballroom with up to 2435 seats (formerly 2740) could be transformed into an auditorium completely furnished with fixed rows of seats and elevation or into a banquet hall with a flat floor in the area of the parquet in front of the stage thanks to the special \"tilting parquet\".\n\nThe banquet hall was optimized for multi-functionality in its room acoustics and had been adapted for use as a concert hall or for electronically amplified music or speech events through variable absorption or reflection surfaces.\n\nIn addition to the large hall, the Kulturpalast had a studio theatre with 192 seats, seminar, rehearsal and performance rooms, foyer levels, office wings and a restaurant with conference facilities.\n\nOutwardly, the ballroom is distinguished by the roof, which protrudes from the cuboid base structure and has the base area of a symmetrical trapezoid.\n\n=== Wall Painting ===\n[[File:Der Weg der roten Fahne-Inschriften.jpg|thumb|Inscriptions on the wall painting]]\nThe 30 meter by 10.5 meter mural ''Der Weg der [[Red flag (politics)|Roten Fahne]]'' (The way of the red flag) on the west side of the building has been designated a cultural monument since 2001. In 1968 Gerhard Bondzin was commissioned to develop the designs. The mural was realized until 1969 by a working group of the [[Dresden Academy of Fine Arts]]. The working title was: \u201e1849 - 1969: 120 Jahre Kampf der revolution\u00e4ren Kr\u00e4fte der Stadt f\u00fcr Fortschritt und Sozialismus\u201c (1849 - 1969: 120 years of struggle of the revolutionary forces of the city for progress and socialism).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saechsische.de/der-weg-der-roten-fahne-haelt-fuer-die-ewigkeit-2658892.html|title=\"Der Weg der roten Fahne\" h\u00e4lt f\u00fcr die Ewigkeit|website=www.saechsische.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> In addition to Bondzin (artistic director), the artists' collective included Alfred Hesse (participation in transmission work), Gerhard Stengel (artistic technology), Gerhard Pr\u00e4kelt (architect), Emil Spiess (study organization), Martin H\u00e4nisch (type design), Wolfgang Richter (specialist instructor) and students in the 3rd and 4th year of the mural design course. It consists of colored glass on concrete slabs that have been electrostatically coated - a technique that was used for the first time in a mural of this size.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kober|first=Rudolf|title=Wandbilder in der Deutschen Demokratischen Republik|publisher=|year=1987|isbn=|volume=5|location=Berlin, Germany|pages=24\u201333, 39|language=german}}</ref>\nThe text in the mural reads: ''\u201eDie Befreiung der Arbeiterklasse kann nur das Werk der Arbeiterklasse selbst sein. Leben wird unser Programm. Trotz alledem wir sind der Sieger der Geschichte! Gewidmet dem 20. Jahrestag der DDR. Entstanden in sozialistischer Gemeinschaftsarbeit der Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Dresden\u201c (''The liberation of the working class can only be the work of the working class itself. Life becomes our program. Despite all this, we are the victor of history! Dedicated to the 20th anniversary of the GDR. Created in socialist community work of the Dresden Academy of Fine Arts)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Der_Weg_der_Roten_Fahne|title=Category:Der Weg der Roten Fahne|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe wall frieze Unser sozialistisches Leben by Heinz Drache and Walter Rehn measuring 45 meter \u00d7 1.90 meter on the first floor was preserved during the renovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kulturpalast-dresden.de/de/foyers.html|title=Foyers - Kulturpalast Dresden|website=www.kulturpalast-dresden.de|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Doors ===\n[[File:+Kulturpalast Dresden - Eingangst\u00fcre - (DDR) - Bild 004.jpg|thumb|Kulturpalast Dresden: Entrance door after reconstruction]]\nThe five bronze main entrance doors were created by [[Gerd Jaeger]] in 1969 and represent Dresden's development from a fishing village to a large city. The bronze casting of the doors was carried out by the foundry Pirner & Franz in Dresden.\n\n=== Well ===\nIn front of the building, there are three [[water feature]]s which were created in 1969 on Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe. The fountains were later removed in the course of the construction work for the underground car park at Altmarkt. These were [[terrazzo]] pools measuring 7.90 by 8.55 metres. In each basin there was a jet fountain on an area of 3 by 3 meters, 24 small heap fountains were installed at the edge of the basin.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Kunst im \u00f6ffentlichen Raum|publisher=Kulturamt Dresden|year=1996|isbn=|location=Dresden, Germany|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Views ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" style=\"text-align:left;\">\nDresden Altmarkt Sicht auf Kulturpalast 1 Panorama.jpg|Panorama of the Palace of Culture from the Altmarkt (February 2017)\nAltmarkt dresden kulturpalast2.JPG|View over the Altmarkt to the Kulturpalast, behind it the [[Dresden Frauenkirche]], which was rebuilt until 2005 \nAltmarkt (Dresden)2009 06.jpg|Close-up with Frauenkirche and row building at Wilsdruffer Stra\u00dfe, 2009\n20121008160DR DD Blick v d Frauenkirche Richtung Altmarkt.jpg|View from the Frauenkirche over the reborn Neumarkt, Kulturpalast and Altmarkt, 2012\nDD-Kulturpalast-Foyer.jpg|Foyer of the Kulturpalast\nDD-Kulturpalast-Obergeschoss-1.jpg|First floor with the wall frieze 'Unser sozialistisches Leben' ''Our socialist life''\nDD-Kulturpalast-Bibo-1.jpg|Central Library of the Municipal Libraries\n</gallery>\n\n== Conversion ==\n[[File:DD-Kulturpalast-Saal-04.jpg|thumb|The new concert hall]]\n\n=== Conversion planning ===\n[[File:Dresdner Philharmonie im Kulturpalast 2.jpg|thumb|The Dresden Philharmonic and the organ in the renovated Kulturpalast]]\nIn October 2013 the reconstruction work on the Palace of Culture began.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresden.de/de/rathaus/aktuelles/pressemitteilungen/archiv/2013/10/pm_050.php|title=Baustart im Dresdner Kulturpalast|last=Dresden|website=www.dresden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The festival hall was to be converted into a pure concert hall with a reduced capacity as a venue for the Dresden Philharmonic. The studio stage, seminar rooms and other used areas of the Kulturpalast were to be redesigned as the venue for the Herkuleskeule (Leg of Hercules) and the library operations of the Municipal Library. In addition to cost savings, this was intended to achieve an all-day opening and use of the building by different age and interest groups.\n\n=== Architecture competition ===\nTo achieve the conversion, the state capital announced an architectural competition in which the office of [[Gerkan, Marg and Partners|Gerkan, Marg and Partner]] won the first prize unanimously and with recommendation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresden.de/de/rathaus/aktuelles/pressemitteilungen/archiv/2009/06/pm_110.php|title=Jury ermittelte Siegerentwurf zum Kulturpalastumbau|last=Dresden|website=www.dresden.de|language=de|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The design envisaged a pure concert hall in the shape of a [[vineyard]] (similar to the hall of the [[Gewandhaus]] in [[Leipzig]], Germany), which should offer good conditions for the Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra.\n\n=== Reopening 2017 ===\nAfter reconstruction and renovation, the Kulturpalast was reopened on April 28, 2017, with a festive concert by the Dresden Philharmonic Orchestra.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2017-05-03|title=Ein zauberischer Dunst|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/|journal=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|volume=|pages=12|via=}}</ref> The old festival hall was converted into the new concert hall with a reduced capacity of up to 1800 seats. Thus, the Dresden Philharmonic has regained its traditional venue. The new concert hall is also used by international orchestras for concerts. Its acoustics are praised by musicians, audiences and press alike.\n\nIn addition, the Dresden Municipal Libraries (Central Library) and the Dresden cabaret \"Die Herkuleskeuleule\" have now also found their new home here. This means that the building can be opened and used all day long.\n\nThe problem of an adequate multifunctional hall was not addressed or solved in this context but remains open (as of 2017).\n\n== Organ ==\n=== Jehmlich-Organ from 1970 ===\nThe [[Jehmlich Orgelbau Dresden|Jehmlich company]] installed an organ in the Great Hall as Opus 905 in 1970. A pipe organ in a large state cultural institution was still something special at a time when the socialist cultural policy was slow to open up to music with organ parts.\n\nThe instrument had 24 [[Organ stop|stops]] distributed over two [[Manual (music)|manuals]] and [[Pedal keyboard|pedal]]. The disposition corresponding to a universal organ was developed in cooperation with the Dresden organ scientist Prof. Frank-Harald Gre\u00df. The organ with the dimensions (W \u00d7 H \u00d7 D) 7.4 m \u00d7 7.4 m \u00d7 1.5 m stood on a mobile steel frame on which it could be pushed onto the stage on rails specially laid for this purpose. However, this mobility and the shortage of money set clear limits to the size of the organ, which at that time had a very modest capacity for a hall with well over 2000 seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jehmlich-orgelbau.de/orgelprojekte/cottbus-propsteikirche/|title=Cottbus, Kath. Propsteikirche St. Marien, 2 Manuale 24 Register, Gebr. Jehmlich 1970, Restaurierung 2015|last=Jehmlich|first=Evelyn|website=Jehmlich Orgelbau Dresden|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The pipes stood on three slider chests, the [[tracker action]] was mechanical and the stop action electro-pneumatic.\n\nIn the course of the major reconstruction of the concert hall, the organ was dismantled in 2012 and, after an overhaul, rebuilt in 2015 in the Provost and Parish Church of St. Maria Friedensk\u00f6nigin in [[Cottbus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orgbase.nl/scripts/ogb.exe?database=ob2&%250=2026024&LGE=DE&LIJST=lang&OLC=5005164|title=Orgel Databank {{!}} Beschreibung Orgel|website=orgbase.nl|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''I Main plant''' C\u2013f<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''II Swell''' C\u2013f<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Pedal''' C\u2013f<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|1.\n|Pomerania\n|16\u2032\n|10.\n|Pointed viol\n|8\u2032\n|19.\n|Subba\u00df\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|2.\n|Principal\n|8\u2032\n|11.\n|Dacked\n|8\u2032\n|20.\n|Principalba\u00df\n|8\u2032\n|-\n|3.\n|Reed pipe\n|8\u2032\n|12.\n|Principal\n|4\u2032\n|21.\n|Gemshorn\n|4\u2032\n|-\n|4.\n|Octave\n|4\u2032\n|13.\n|Belt flute\n|4\u2032\n|22.\n|Subordinate clause VI\n|\n|-\n|5.\n|Flat flute\n|2\u2032\n|14.\n|Octave\n|2\u2032\n|23.\n|Trombone\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|6.\n|Noise fifth II\n|\n|15.\n|Sifflute\n|1\u2032\n|24.\n|Clarinet\n|4\u2032\n|-\n|7.\n|Mixture VI\n|\n|16.\n|Sesquialtera II\n|\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"4\" |\n|-\n|8.\n|Solo cymbal II\n|\n|17.\n|Sharp\n|\n|-\n|9.\n|Trumpet\n|8\u2032\n|18.\n|Pipe shawl\n|16\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|}\n* Coupling: II/I, I/P, II/P\n* playing aids: 4 free combinations, tutti, reeds off, single reed stop\n\n=== Eule-Organ from 2017 ===\nOn 8 September 2017 the new concert [[Pipe organ|organ]], built by the company Hermann Eule Orgelbau Bautzen, was inaugurated.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dresdnerphilharmonie.de/media/content/download/programmhefte/2017_09_08_orgeleinweihung.pdf|title=Einweihung der Konzertorgel|last=|first=|date=2017-09-08|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The financing was largely provided by the Dresden Philharmonic Society of Friends, largely under its chairman George Gerard Arnhold.\n\nThe new instrument has 67 stops (4013 sounding pipes) distributed over four manuals and pedal (slider chest). The main part of the instrument measures 14.7 meters in width, 3.3 meters in depth and 8.5 meters in height, and weighs about 20.5 tons. The action is electric, the [[Organ console|console]] is mobile. A special feature of the instrument is the French horn register, which is placed in a separate sill in the II manual and can be played as a solo register from the IV manual. The registers of the freely connectable bombarde mechanism are located in the sill in the III manual.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''I Main plant''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''II Swell''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''III R\u00e9cit-Orchestral''' C\u2013a<sup>3</sup>\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''IV Solo'''\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Pedal''' C\u2013g<sup>1</sup>\n|-\n|1.\n|Principal\n|16\u2032\n|14.\n|Sweetheart. dacked\n|16\u2032\n|29.\n|Viola\n|16\u2032\n|\n|<u>open</u>\n|\n|50.\n|Grand Bourdon\n|32\u2032\n|-\n|2.\n|Principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|15.\n|Violin principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|30.\n|Principal\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|44.\n|Melody\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|51.\n|Open Wood\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|3.\n|Large open Diapason\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|16.\n|Salicional\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|31.\n|Viol d'orchestre\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|45.\n|Tuba sonora\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|''52.''\n|''Principal <small>(= Nr. 1)</small>''\n|''16\u2032''\n|-\n|4.\n|Flood major\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|17.\n|Double flute\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|32.\n|Concert Flute\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|\n|<u>swellable</u>\n|\n|53.\n|Violon\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|5.\n|Cello\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|18.\n|Reed pipe\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|33.\n|Tender-headed\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|46.\n|French Horn <small>(=no. 28)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|54.\n|Subbass <small>(Ext. Nr. 50)</small>\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|6.\n|Narrator\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|19.\n|Violin octave\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|34.\n|Aeoline\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''Bombarde'''\n|''55.''\n|''Bass dacked <small>(= no. 14)</small>''\n|''16\u2032''\n|-\n|7.\n|Octave\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|20.\n|Flute\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|35.\n|Vox coelestis ''<small>(from G)</small>'' {{0}}\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|47.\n|Bombard\n|16\u2032\n|''56.''\n|''Dulcianabass <small>(= no. 29)</small>'' {{0}}\n|16\u2032\n|-\n|8.\n|Hollow flute\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|21.\n|Nasard\n|{{0}}{{Frac|2|2|3}}\u2032\n|36.\n|Quinta tone\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|48.\n|Trumpet harmonique\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|57.\n|Octavbass\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|9.\n|Fifth\n|{{0}}{{Frac|2|2|3}}\u2032\n|22.\n|Flautino\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|37.\n|Fugara\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|49.\n|Clairon harmonique\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|58.\n|Violoncello <small>(Ext. no. 53)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|10.\n|Octave\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|23.\n|Third\n|{{0}}{{Frac|1|3|5}}\u2032\n|38.\n|Flute octaviante\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"9\" |\n|59.\n|Bass flute <small>(Ext. no. 50)</small>\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|11.\n|Mixtur IV\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|24.\n|Progressive III\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|39.\n|Octavin\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|''60.''\n|''Salicetbass <small>(= no. 16)</small>''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|-\n|12.\n|Cornet III\u2013V\n|{{0}}2\u2032\n|25.\n|Cor anglais\n|16\u2032\n|40.\n|Viol-Cornett III\n|{{0}}{{Frac|3|1|5}}\u2032\n|''61.''\n|''Bourdonbass <small>(= no. 30)</small>''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|-\n|13.\n|trumpet\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|26.\n|Cornopean\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|41.\n|Plein jeu V\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|62.\n|Octave <small>(Ext. no. 57)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"5\" |\n|27.\n|Clarinet\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|42.\n|Orchestral Oboe\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|63.\n|Bass flute <small>(Ext. no. 50)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|-\n|''28.''\n|''French Horn (separately swellable)''\n|{{0}}''8\u2032''\n|43.\n|Voix Humaine\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|64.\n|Contratrombone\n|32\u2032\n|-\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|\n|''Tremulant''\n|\n|65.\n|Trombone <small>(Ext. no. 64)</small>\n|16\u2032\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n| colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n|66.\n|Bass trombone\n|{{0}}8\u2032\n|-\n|67.\n|Clairon <small>(Ext. no. 64)</small>\n|{{0}}4\u2032\n|}\n* Pair up:\n** 10 normal couplings: IV/I, III/I, II/I, III/II, III/I, II/I, I/P, II/P, III/P, IV/P\n** 5 Normal couplers bombarde movement (to all manual movements and the pedal)\n** 5 Sub-octave couplings: III/III, III/I, II/II, II/I, I/I\n** 5 super-octave couplings: III/III, III/I, II/II, II/I, IV/P\n* Game help\n* slider chests, 14 large windchests, 18 single tone chests\n* 10 magazine bellows, 3 pre-bellows, 2 normal pressure and 1 high-pressure fan\n* electric playing and register [[tracker action]] action, BUS system, setting system Eule, MIDI recording function\n* Tuning pitch: 443&nbsp;Hz at 21&nbsp;\u00b0C, type of tuning: equal floating\n* 4,013 sounding pipes, of which 223 pipes from 6 registers in the prospectus (there plus 96 blind pipes).\n* largest pipe: Contra trombone 32\u2032, C, 9.23 m, largest prospect pipe: Principal 16\u2032, 6.73 m<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Literature ==\n* Birk Engmann: ''Bauen f\u00fcr die Ewigkeit: Monumentalarchitektur des zwanzigsten Jahrhunderts und St\u00e4dtebau in Leipzig in den f\u00fcnfziger Jahren.'' Sax-Verlag, Beucha, Germany, 2006, {{ISBN|3-934544-81-9}}, German\n* Wolfgang H\u00e4nsch: ''Haus der sozialistischen Kultur.'' In: ''Deutsche Architektur.'' Issue 4, 1968, P. 212\u2013671, German\n* Meinhard von Gerkan, Stephan Sch\u00fctz (Ed.): ''Kulturpalast Dresden.'' Publisher Jovis Verlag, Berlin 2017, {{ISBN|978-3-86859-484-3}}, German\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Kulturpalast, Dresden|Kulturpalast (Dresden)}}\n* [htt