type=Liner Notes|publisher=[[Talkin' Loud]]}}</ref>\n{{Div col}}\n*[[Roni Size]] (Ryan Williams) \u2013 writing, production, keyboards\n*[[Onallee]] (Tracey Bowen) \u2013 vocals, writing\n*[[Dynamite MC]] (Dominic Smith) \u2013 vocals, writing\n*[[DJ Die]] (Daniel Kausman) \u2013 writing, production\n*DJ Suv (Paul Southey) \u2013 writing, production\n*[[Krust]] (Kirk Thompson) \u2013 writing, production\n*Clive Deemer \u2013 drums\n*Si John \u2013 bass\n*[[Bahamadia]] (Antonia Reed) \u2013 vocals\n*Tyrrell \u2013 guitar\n*Adrian Place \u2013 saxophone\n*[[Roisin Murphy]] - vocals (sampled)\n*Gilles Peterson \u2013 A&R\n*Paul Martin \u2013 A&R\n*Intro. London \u2013 design\n*Vikki Jackman \u2013 photography\n*Simon Goffe \u2013 management\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable unsortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Organisation\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"1\"| 1997\n| [[Mercury Prize]]\n| Mercury Album of the Year\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|.<br><ref>\n{{Cite web|title=It is Size that counts as Roni wins Mercury prize|website=[[The Independent]]|language=en|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/it-is-size-that-counts-as-roni-wins-mercury-prize-1247754.html|accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (1997\u201398)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands ([[MegaCharts]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Roni Size - Reprazent - dutchcarts.nl|work=[[MegaCharts]]|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Roni+Size&titel=Reprazent+%2F+New+Forms&cat=a|accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n|96\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ]])<ref>{{cite web|title=Charts.org.nz - Roni Size / Reprazent|work=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Roni+Size&titel=Reprazent+%2F+New+Forms&cat=a|accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n|37\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Albums Chart]] ([[Official Charts Company]])<ref name=\"occ\"/>\n|8\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Heatseekers Albums]] (''[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|title=Roni Size/Reprazent Chart History|work=[[Billboard charts]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/roni-size-reprazent/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n|36\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Roni Size/Reprazent|title=New Forms|award=Platinum|certyear=2013|relyear=1997}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Reprazent}}\n\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n[[Category:Roni Size albums]]\n[[Category:Mercury Prize-winning albums]]\n[[Category:Talkin' Loud albums]]\n", "name_user": "Holiday56", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Forms"}
{"title_page": "Colin Cooper", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Colin Cooper\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Colin Terence Cooper\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1967|2|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Durham, England|Durham]], England\n| height =\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1984\u20131991 | clubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]         | caps1 = 188 | goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 1991\u20131993 | clubs2 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                   | caps2 = 77  | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 1993\u20131998 | clubs3 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] | caps3 = 180 | goals3 = 20\n| years4 = 1998\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]         | caps4 = 158 | goals4 = 5\n| years5 = 2004      | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] (loan)    | caps5 = 3   | goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps = 606 | totalgoals = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 1988\u20131989 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 8 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1995      | nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]              | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2009 | managerclubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears2 = 2011 | managerclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears3 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs3 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] \n}}\n'''Colin Terence Cooper''' (born 28 February 1967) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]]. Cooper spent most of his playing career at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. Prior to his appointment at Hartlepool, Cooper was part of the Middlesbrough coaching staff after leaving his role of assistant manager at Bradford City.\n\n==Playing career==\nHe played as a centre back, but was equally useful at full-back. He spent the first seven years of his professional career contracted to Middlesbrough, making 188 league appearances and scoring six league goals in the process. During this time, he helped Middlesbrough through [[liquidation]] in 1986.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn the summer of 1991, he was transferred to Division Two side (renamed Division One and then the [[Football League Championship]]) [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] for the sum of \u00a3300,000 spending two successful seasons at The Den.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAfter impressing several big name clubs, he decided to move to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in 1993 for \u00a31,700,000. It was at Forest where Colin arguably played the best football of his career, his form earning him two [[England national football team|England]] caps in 1995.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAfter experiencing the joys of two promotions and the heart-break of a relegation, \"Super Coops\" was re-purchased by his first club, Middlesbrough, in a \u00a32,500,000 deal. Many people questioned the signing of the stalwart from Nottingham Forest, but Colin proved to many people that he was more than capable of playing [[FA Premier League|Premier League]] football. He maintained a consistent level of play throughout the seven years that he spent with Middlesbrough, and could always be relied upon to do a job. He almost gave up the game in 2002 after his son, Finlay, died in an accident at the family home<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/son-of-footballer-dies-choking-on-toy-671504.html\n|title=Son of footballer dies choking on toy\n|work=[[The Independent]]\n|date=28 January 2002 |accessdate=12 March 2010\n| location=London\n| first=Arifa\n| last=Akbar}}</ref> just hours after their victory over Manchester United in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/1780868.stm\n|title=Boro sink Man Utd\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=26 January 2002 |accessdate=12 March 2010}}</ref> In 2003\u201304, he spent some time on loan with [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. Cooper was part of Middlesbrough's [[2003\u201304 Football League Cup|2004 League Cup]]-winning team. Despite not making the squad for the final<ref>{{cite news|title=Boro lift Carling Cup|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3507795.stm|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 February 2004}}</ref> he appeared in the earlier rounds.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|1633|2003|name=Colin Cooper|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Cooper was awarded a one-year contract extension, which saw him play at the age of 39. His final season with Middlesbrough, 2005\u201306, saw Boro reach the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]]. However, he made just one appearance all campaign, coming on as a late substitute on the last day of the season against Fulham.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4957456.stm\n|title=Fulham 1\u20130 Middlesbrough\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=7 May 2006 |accessdate=12 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCooper made his England international debut in a 3\u20133 draw against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersC/BioCooperCT.html\n|title=Colin Cooper\n|publisher=England Football Online}}</ref> He gained two caps for the England national team and made 8 for the Under-21 side where he finished runners-up with the U21s in the 1988 Tournoi Espoirs de Toulon tournament.\n\n==Coaching==\nAfter he retired from playing, in June 2006, Cooper was officially given a job with the [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] coaching staff, as the Reserve team coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/5071614.stm |title=Southgate shuffles coaching staff |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 June 2006 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Following [[Steve Round]]'s departure from the club in December 2006, Cooper was promoted to a more active role with the first team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2006/12/15/boro-promotion-for-cooper-471476/ |title=Boro promotion for Cooper |publisher=Metro |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Following the departure of [[Malcolm Crosby]] on 17 June 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11680_5385687,00.html |title=Crosby leaves Boro |publisher=Sky Sports |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Richard |last=Bailey}}</ref> Cooper was promoted to assistant manager at Middlesbrough.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2330334/Colin-Cooper-appointed-Hartlepool-manager.html |title=Hartlepool hire ex-Middlesbrough star Cooper as their sixth boss in five years |work=Daily Mail|date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Graeme |last=Yorke}}</ref> On 22 October 2009, following the departure of manager [[Gareth Southgate]], Cooper was appointed caretaker manager at Middlesbrough.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/22/colin-cooper-middlesbrough-gordon-strachan |title=Colin Cooper to lead Boro at Preston but Gordon Strachan waits in the wings |work=The Guardian|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Louise |last=Taylor}}</ref> However, he was only employed in this position for four days, as [[Gordon Strachan]] was announced as the new manager on 26 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/8319489.stm |title=Strachan named Middlesbrough boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Cooper's solitary match in charge was a 2\u20132 draw with [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 24 October 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8316497.stm |title=Preston 2\u20132 Middlesbrough |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> In May 2010, Cooper was relieved of all duties at Middlesbrough by Strachan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/8694757.stm |title=Middlesbrough roles for Gary McAllister and Jim Blyth |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2011, Cooper was appointed as assistant to interim manager [[Peter Jackson (footballer born 1961)|Peter Jackson]] at [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/9419737.stm |title=Bradford City appoint Colin Cooper as assistant manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/8899175.Cooper_made_to_feel_like_one_of_the_family_at_Valley_Parade/ |title=Bradford City No 2 Cooper made to feel like one of the family at Valley Parade |date=2011-03-10 |accessdate=2011-03-10 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> Jackson was subsequently appointed full-time manager on 25 May 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/9045212.Finally__Jackson_appointed_Bradford_City_manager/ |title=Finally, Jackson appointed Bradford City manager |publisher=Bradford Telegraph and Argus |date=25 May 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> but he resigned on 25 August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14670814 |title=Bradford City manager Peter Jackson resigns |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> resulting in Cooper taking over as caretaker manager.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10266~2432708,00.html | title=Cooper to take charge on Saturday | publisher=Bradford City Football Club official website | date=26 August 2011 | accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> winning his first game 4\u20132 against [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]. [[Phil Parkinson]] was appointed as Jackson's permanent successor,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14692940 |title=Phil Parkinson appointed Bradford City manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 August 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and on 8 September 2011, Cooper left Bradford to rejoin Middlesbrough and take up a coaching role with Middlesbrough's under-18 side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14838588 |title=Colin Cooper set for Middlesbrough after Bradford exit |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2013, he became manager at [[Football League Two]] side [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], replacing [[John Hughes (footballer born 1964)|John Hughes]], who had been sacked the previous month.<ref name=\"hartlepool appointment\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22511287 |title=Hartlepool United appoint Colin Cooper as new boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> He named fellow ex-Middlesbrough player [[Craig Hignett]] as his assistant manager.<ref name=\"hartlepool appointment\"/> After winning four out of five league games in October, Cooper won the [[Football League Two|Sky Bet League Two]] Manager of the Month Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/sport/football/hartlepool-utd/hartlepool-united-s-colin-cooper-and-luke-james-win-manager-and-player-of-the-month-1-6225441 |work=Hartlepool Mail|date=7 November 2013 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nCooper resigned as Hartlepool United manager on 4 October 2014, after a 3\u20130 home defeat by [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]], which left the club at the bottom of the League Two table.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29493227|title=Hartlepool United: Colin Cooper resigns as manager|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 October 2014|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nCooper was a regular guest on the ITV late night football review programme ''[[Soccer Night]]'', which was hosted by [[Roger Tames]]. During this programme, three legendary figures, representing one of each of the North-East's top three clubs ([[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]), come to the studio and discuss recent footballing events.\n\n==Charity work==\nIn 2006, Colin and his wife Julie, formed the charity the Finlay Cooper Fund, named after his son who died in a tragic accident in 2002, which raises money for children's causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finlaycooperfund.co.uk/about-us/ |title=About us |publisher=Finlay Cooper Fund |accessdate=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316061511/http://www.finlaycooperfund.co.uk/about-us/ |archive-date=16 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2013, Colin and 12 others (which included [[Craig Hignett]] and [[Jeff Stelling]]) climbed [[Mount Kilimanjaro]] for charity;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/story/2013-06-13/charity-team-conquer-kilimanjaro/ |title=Charity team conquer Kilimanjaro |publisher=ITV News |date=13 June 2013 |accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> the climb raised \u00a3100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/news/local/hartlepool-united-manager-s-kilimanjaro-trek-raises-100-000-for-charity-1-6194720 |title=Hartlepool United manager's Kilimanjaro trek raises \u00a3100,000 for charity |work=Hartlepool Mail|date=29 October 2013 |accessdate=3 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030012411/http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/news/local/hartlepool-united-manager-s-kilimanjaro-trek-raises-100-000-for-charity-1-6194720 |archive-date=30 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n===Playing career===\n''Statistics for league appearances only''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:15em\" |Club !!Season !!Games !!Goals !!Division\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" valign=\"top\" | [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| 1984-85 || 0  || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1985-86 || 11 || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1986-87 || 46 || 0 || Division 3\n|-\n| 1987-88 || 43 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1988-89 || 35 || 2 || Division 1\n|-\n| 1989-90 || 21 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1990-91 || 32 || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" | [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n| 1991-92 || 36 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1992-93 || 41 || 4 || Division 1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"top\" | [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| 1993-94 || 37 || 7 || Division 1\n|-\n| 1994-95 || 35 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1995-96 || 37 || 5 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1996-97 || 36 || 2 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1997-98 || 35 || 5 || Division 1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" valign=\"top\" | [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| 1998-99 || 32 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1999\u20132000 || 26 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2000-01 || 27 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2001-02 || 18 || 2 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2002-03 || 20 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2003-04 || 19 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" valign=\"top\" | [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| 2003-04 || 3  || 0 || Division 1 (on loan)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" | [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| 2004-05 || 15 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2005-06 || 1  || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" valign=\"top\" | Total\n!         !! 606 !! 37 !!\n|}\n\n===Managerial career===\n{{updated|4 October 2014}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Colin Cooper|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=2175|work=[[Racing Post|Soccerbase]]|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] (caretaker)\n|align=left|20 October 2009\n|align=left|26 October 2009\n{{WDL|2|1|1|0|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (caretaker)\n|align=left|25 August 2011\n|align=left|29 August 2011\n{{WDL|1|1|0|0|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]]\n|align=left|24 May 2013\n|align=left|4 October 2014\n{{WDL|65|19|14|32|decimals=1}}\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n{{WDLtot|68|21|15|32|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n;Middlesbrough\n*1986-87 Division 3 runners-up (Promotion to Division Two)\n*1987-88 Division 2 third place (Promotion to Division One)\n*[[Full Members Cup|Zenith Data Systems Cup]]: Runner up 1989/90 with [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n*[[2003\u201304 Football League Cup]]\n\n;Nottingham Forest\n*1993-94 Division 1 runners up (Promotion to Premier League)\n*1994-95 Premier League 3rd place (Qualification for UEFA Cup)\n*1997-98 Division 1 Champions (Promotion to Premier League)\n\n;England U21s\n*Tournoi Espoirs de Toulon (U21) runners-up 1988\n\n;Individual\n*[[Football League Two]] Manager of the Month Award: October 2013\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{1992\u201393 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{1993\u201394 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{1997\u201398 Football League First Division PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Nottingham Forest F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Colin Cooper managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Middlesbrough F.C. managers}}\n{{Bradford City A.F.C. managers}}\n{{Hartlepool United F.C. managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Colin}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Durham, England]]\n[[Category:Footballers from County Durham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Millwall F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Hartlepool United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Outfield association footballers who played in goal]]\n[[Category:English football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Colin Cooper\n| image = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Colin Terence Cooper\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1967|2|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Durham, England|Durham]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| position = [[Defender (football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1984\u20131991 | clubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]         | caps1 = 188 | goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 1991\u20131993 | clubs2 = [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]                   | caps2 = 77  | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 1993\u20131998 | clubs3 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] | caps3 = 180 | goals3 = 20\n| years4 = 1998\u20132006 | clubs4 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]         | caps4 = 158 | goals4 = 5\n| years5 = 2004      | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] (loan)    | caps5 = 3   | goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps = 606 | totalgoals = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 1988\u20131989 | nationalteam1 = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 8 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1995      | nationalteam2 = [[England national football team|England]]              | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2009 | managerclubs1 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears2 = 2011 | managerclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (caretaker)\n| manageryears3 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs3 = [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] \n}}\n'''Colin Terence Cooper''' (born 28 February 1967) is an English former professional [[association football|footballer]]. Cooper spent most of his playing career at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]. Prior to his appointment at Hartlepool, Cooper was part of the Middlesbrough coaching staff after leaving his role of assistant manager at Bradford City.\n\n==Playing career==\nHe played as a centre back, but was equally useful at full-back.  He spent the first seven years of his professional career contracted to Middlesbrough, making 188 league appearances and scoring six league goals in the process.  During this time, he helped Middlesbrough through [[liquidation]] in 1986.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn the summer of 1991, he was transferred to Division Two side (renamed Division One and then the [[Football League Championship]]) [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] for the sum of \u00a3300,000 spending two successful seasons at The Den.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAfter impressing several big name clubs, he decided to move to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in 1993 for \u00a31,700,000. It was at Forest where Colin arguably played the best football of his career, his form earning him two [[England national football team|England]] caps in 1995.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nAfter experiencing the joys of two promotions and the heart-break of a relegation, \"Super Coops\" was re-purchased by his first club, Middlesbrough, in a \u00a32,500,000 deal. Many people questioned the signing of the stalwart from Nottingham Forest, but Colin proved to many people that he was more than capable of playing [[FA Premier League|Premier League]] football. He maintained a consistent level of play throughout the seven years that he spent with Middlesbrough, and could always be relied upon to do a job. He almost gave up the game in 2002 after his son, Finlay, died in an accident at the family home<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/son-of-footballer-dies-choking-on-toy-671504.html\n|title=Son of footballer dies choking on toy\n|work=[[The Independent]]\n|date=28 January 2002 |accessdate=12 March 2010\n| location=London\n| first=Arifa\n| last=Akbar}}</ref> just hours after their victory over Manchester United in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/1780868.stm\n|title=Boro sink Man Utd\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=26 January 2002 |accessdate=12 March 2010}}</ref> In 2003-04, he spent some time on loan with [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. Cooper was part of Middlesbrough's [[2003\u201304 Football League Cup|2004 League Cup]]-winning team. Despite not making the squad for the final<ref>{{cite news|title=Boro lift Carling Cup|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3507795.stm|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=29 February 2004}}</ref> he appeared in the earlier rounds.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|1633|2003|name=Colin Cooper|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Cooper was awarded a one-year contract extension, which saw him play at the age of 39. His final season with Middlesbrough, 2005\u201306, saw Boro reach the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]]. However, he made just one appearance all campaign, coming on as a late substitute on the last day of the season against Fulham.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4957456.stm\n|title=Fulham 1\u20130 Middlesbrough\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|date=7 May 2006 |accessdate=12 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCooper made his England international debut in a 3-3 draw against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersC/BioCooperCT.html\n|title=Colin Cooper\n|publisher=England Football Online}}</ref> He gained two caps for the England national team and made 8 for the Under-21 side where he finished runners-up with the U21s in the 1988 Tournoi Espoirs de Toulon tournament.\n\n==Coaching==\nAfter he retired from playing, in June 2006, Cooper was officially given a job with the [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] coaching staff, as the Reserve team coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/5071614.stm |title=Southgate shuffles coaching staff |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 June 2006 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Following [[Steve Round]]'s departure from the club in December 2006, Cooper was promoted to a more active role with the first team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://metro.co.uk/2006/12/15/boro-promotion-for-cooper-471476/ |title=Boro promotion for Cooper |publisher=Metro |date=15 December 2006 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Following the departure of [[Malcolm Crosby]] on 17 June 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11680_5385687,00.html |title=Crosby leaves Boro |publisher=Sky Sports |date=17 June 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Richard |last=Bailey}}</ref> Cooper was promoted to assistant manager at Middlesbrough.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2330334/Colin-Cooper-appointed-Hartlepool-manager.html |title=Hartlepool hire ex-Middlesbrough star Cooper as their sixth boss in five years |work=Daily Mail|date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Graeme |last=Yorke}}</ref> On 22 October 2009, following the departure of manager [[Gareth Southgate]], Cooper was appointed caretaker manager at Middlesbrough.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/22/colin-cooper-middlesbrough-gordon-strachan |title=Colin Cooper to lead Boro at Preston but Gordon Strachan waits in the wings |work=The Guardian|date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Louise |last=Taylor}}</ref> However, he was only employed in this position for four days, as [[Gordon Strachan]] was announced as the new manager on 26 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/8319489.stm |title=Strachan named Middlesbrough boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Cooper's solitary match in charge was a 2-2 draw with [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 24 October 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/8316497.stm |title=Preston 2\u20132 Middlesbrough |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 October 2009 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> In May 2010, Cooper was relieved of all duties at Middlesbrough by Strachan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/8694757.stm |title=Middlesbrough roles for Gary McAllister and Jim Blyth |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March 2011, Cooper was appointed as assistant to interim manager [[Peter Jackson (footballer born 1961)|Peter Jackson]] at [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/9419737.stm |title=Bradford City appoint Colin Cooper as assistant manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/8899175.Cooper_made_to_feel_like_one_of_the_family_at_Valley_Parade/ |title=Bradford City No 2 Cooper made to feel like one of the family at Valley Parade |date=2011-03-10 |accessdate=2011-03-10 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> Jackson was subsequently appointed full-time manager on 25 May 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/9045212.Finally__Jackson_appointed_Bradford_City_manager/ |title=Finally, Jackson appointed Bradford City manager |publisher=Bradford Telegraph and Argus |date=25 May 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013 |first=Simon |last=Parker}}</ref> but he resigned on 25 August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14670814 |title=Bradford City manager Peter Jackson resigns |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> resulting in Cooper taking over as caretaker manager.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.co.uk/page/News/0,,10266~2432708,00.html | title=Cooper to take charge on Saturday | publisher=Bradford City Football Club official website | date=26 August 2011 | accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> winning his first game 4\u20132 against [[Barnet F.C.|Barnet]]. [[Phil Parkinson]] was appointed as Jackson's permanent successor,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14692940 |title=Phil Parkinson appointed Bradford City manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 August 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and on 8 September 2011, Cooper left Bradford to rejoin Middlesbrough and take up a coaching role with Middlesbrough's under-18 side.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14838588 |title=Colin Cooper set for Middlesbrough after Bradford exit |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2011 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 May 2013, he became manager at [[Football League Two]] side [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], replacing [[John Hughes (footballer born 1964)|John Hughes]], who had been sacked the previous month.<ref name=\"hartlepool appointment\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22511287 |title=Hartlepool United appoint Colin Cooper as new boss |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2013 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> He named fellow ex-Middlesbrough player [[Craig Hignett]] as his assistant manager.<ref name=\"hartlepool appointment\"/> After winning four out of five league games in October, Cooper won the [[Football League Two|Sky Bet League Two]] Manager of the Month Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/sport/football/hartlepool-utd/hartlepool-united-s-colin-cooper-and-luke-james-win-manager-and-player-of-the-month-1-6225441 |work=Hartlepool Mail|date=7 November 2013 |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nCooper resigned as Hartlepool United manager on 4 October 2014, after a 3\u20130 home defeat by [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]], which left the club at the bottom of the League Two table.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29493227|title=Hartlepool United: Colin Cooper resigns as manager|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 October 2014|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nCooper was a regular guest on the ITV late night football review programme ''[[Soccer Night]]'', which was hosted by [[Roger Tames]]. During this programme, three legendary figures, representing one of each of the North-East's top three clubs ([[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]), come to the studio and discuss recent footballing events.\n\n==Charity work==\nIn 2006, Colin and his wife Julie, formed the charity the Finlay Cooper Fund, named after his son who died in a tragic accident in 2002, which raises money for children's causes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finlaycooperfund.co.uk/about-us/ |title=About us |publisher=Finlay Cooper Fund |accessdate=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316061511/http://www.finlaycooperfund.co.uk/about-us/ |archive-date=16 March 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2013, Colin and 12 others (which included [[Craig Hignett]] and [[Jeff Stelling]]) climbed [[Mount Kilimanjaro]] for charity;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/story/2013-06-13/charity-team-conquer-kilimanjaro/ |title=Charity team conquer Kilimanjaro |publisher=ITV News |date=13 June 2013 |accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> the climb raised \u00a3100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/news/local/hartlepool-united-manager-s-kilimanjaro-trek-raises-100-000-for-charity-1-6194720 |title=Hartlepool United manager's Kilimanjaro trek raises \u00a3100,000 for charity |work=Hartlepool Mail|date=29 October 2013 |accessdate=3 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030012411/http://www.hartlepoolmail.co.uk/news/local/hartlepool-united-manager-s-kilimanjaro-trek-raises-100-000-for-charity-1-6194720 |archive-date=30 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n\n===Playing career===\n''Statistics for league appearances only''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:15em\" |Club !!Season !!Games !!Goals !!Division\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" valign=\"top\" | [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| 1984-85 || 0  || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1985-86 || 11 || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1986-87 || 46 || 0 || Division 3\n|-\n| 1987-88 || 43 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1988-89 || 35 || 2 || Division 1\n|-\n| 1989-90 || 21 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1990-91 || 32 || 0 || Division 2\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" | [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]]\n| 1991-92 || 36 || 2 || Division 2\n|-\n| 1992-93 || 41 || 4 || Division 1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" valign=\"top\" | [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| 1993-94 || 37 || 7 || Division 1\n|-\n| 1994-95 || 35 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1995-96 || 37 || 5 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1996-97 || 36 || 2 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1997-98 || 35 || 5 || Division 1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" valign=\"top\" | [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| 1998-99 || 32 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 1999\u20132000 || 26 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2000-01 || 27 || 1 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2001-02 || 18 || 2 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2002-03 || 20 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| 2003-04 || 19 || 0 || Premier League\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" valign=\"top\" | [[S