{"title_page": "Calculator input methods", "text_new": "{{Original research|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019|cs1-dates=y}}\nThere are various ways in which [[calculator]]s interpret keystrokes. These can be categorized into two main types:\n\n* On a '''single-step''' or '''immediate-execution calculator''', the user presses a key for each operation, calculating all the intermediate results, before the final value is shown.<ref>Microsoft\u2019s Windows Operating System Calculator Accessory; 2001. Available on a Windows PC at: Start/All Programs/Accessories/Calculator.</ref><ref>MotionNET [http://www.motionnet.com/calculator Calculator page on the Internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501082324/http://www.motionnet.com/calculator/ |date=1 May 2009 }}; 2006.</ref><ref>Flow Simulation Ltd [http://www.calculator.org/jcalc98.html Virtual Calc98 page on the Internet]; 2008.</ref>\n* On an '''expression''' or '''formula calculator''', one types in an expression and then presses a key, such as \"=\" or \"Enter\", to evaluate the expression.<ref>Formula Calculators Pty Ltd [Home page on the Internet]; 2009.</ref><ref>Moisey Oysgelt [http://www.alemoi.com/math JavaScript Formula Calculator page on the Internet]; 2000.</ref><ref>Haxial Software Pty Ltd [http://www.haxial.com/products/calculator Calculator Product page on the Internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428221125/http://www.haxial.com/products/calculator/ |date=28 April 2009 }}; 2001</ref> There are various systems for typing in an expression, as described below.\n\n=={{anchor|Chain|AES}}Immediate execution==\n[[File:TI-108.jpg|thumb|208x208px|The [[TI-108]] is a simple four-function calculator which uses single-step execution.]]\nThe '''immediate execution''' mode of operation (also known as '''single-step''', '''algebraic entry system''' ('''AES''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\">{{cite book |title=Algorithms for RPN calculators |url=https://archive.org/details/algorithmsforrpn0000ball |url-access=registration |first=John A. |last=Ball |date=1978 |edition=1 |publisher=[[Wiley-Interscience]], [[John Wiley & Sons, Inc.]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA |isbn=0-471-03070-8}}</ref> or '''chain calculation''' mode) is commonly employed on most general-purpose calculators. In most simple four-function calculators, such as the [[Windows Calculator|Windows calculator]] in Standard mode and those included with most early [[Operating system|operating systems]], each [[binary operation]] is executed as soon as the next operator is pressed, and therefore the [[order of operations]] in a mathematical expression is not taken into account. [[Scientific calculators]], including the Scientific mode in the Windows calculator and most modern software calculators, have buttons for brackets and ''can'' take order of operation into account. Also, for [[unary operation]]s, like \u221a or ''x''<sup>2</sup>, the number is entered first, then the operator; this is largely because the display screens on these kinds of calculators are generally composed entirely of [[Seven-segment display|seven-segment characters]] and thus capable  of displaying only numbers, not the functions associated with them. This mode of operation also makes it impossible to change the expression being input without clearing the display entirely.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 7\n\n7\n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n\n{{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|x}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}}{{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>5 - 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|\u2212}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 4 \n|-\n| <math>15 + 10 + 10 + 10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12\n|}\n\nThe first and second example have been given twice. The first version is for simple calculators, showing how it is necessary to rearrange operands in order to get the correct result. The second version is for [[scientific calculator|scientific calculators]], where operator precedence is observed.\n\nImmediate-execution calculators are based on a mixture of infix and postfix notation: binary operations are done as infix, but unary operations are postfix. Because operators are applied one-at-a-time, the user must work out which operator key to use at each stage, and this can lead to problems.<ref>{{cite web |author=Harold Thimbleby |url=http://www.uclic.ucl.ac.uk/harold/srf/allcalcs.pdf |title=A new calculator and why it is necessary |publisher=Computing Science, Middlesex University, London, UK |date=September 1998 |accessdate=2009-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207044654/http://www.uclic.ucl.ac.uk/harold/srf/allcalcs.pdf |archivedate=2007-02-07 }}</ref><ref>Neville Holmes. [http://standards.computer.org/sabminutes/2003Wint/Truth%20and%20Clarity%20in%20Arithmetic%20-%20Neville%20Holmes.pdf Truth and Clarity in Arithmetic] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007234721/http://standards.computer.org/sabminutes/2003Wint/Truth%20and%20Clarity%20in%20Arithmetic%20-%20Neville%20Holmes.pdf |date=7 October 2006 }}, University of Tasmania; 2003.</ref> When discussing these problems, Professor [[Harold Thimbleby]] has pointed out that button-operated calculators \"require numbers and operation signs to be punched in a certain order, and mistakes are easy to make and hard to spot\".<ref>[http://www.physorg.com/news4773.html Professor devises easier calculator]; www.physorg.com. June 2005.</ref>\n\nProblems can occur because, for anything but the simplest calculation, in order to work out the value of a written formula, the user of a button-operated calculator is required to:\n* Rearrange the formula so that the value can be calculated by pressing buttons one at a time, while taking operator precedence and parentheses into account.\n* Use memory buttons to ensure that operations are applied in the correct order.\n* Use the special buttons {{keypress|\u00b1}} and {{keypress|1/''x''}}, that do not correspond to operations in the formula, for non-commutative operators.\n\nMistakes can be hard to spot because:\n* For the above reasons, the sequence of button presses may bear little resemblance to the original formula.\n* The operation carried out when a button is pressed is not always the same as the button, but could be a previously entered operation.\n\n[[File:Calculator-TI-30XA-rev2015.jpg|thumb|This TI-30XA scientific calculator uses immediate execution. It has a one-line, seven-segmented display, and cannot display operands or allow the entries to be edited.]]\n\n===Examples of difficulties===\n\nThe simplest example given by Professor Thimbleby of a possible problem when using an immediate-execution calculator is 4\u202f\u00d7\u202f(\u22125).<ref>Reference 11, section 2.</ref> As a written formula the value of this is \u221220 because the minus sign is intended to indicate a negative number, rather than a subtraction, and this is the way that it would be interpreted by a formula calculator.\n\nOn an immediate-execution calculator, depending on which keys are used and the order in which they are pressed, the result for this calculation may be different. Also there are differences between calculators in the way a given sequence of button presses is interpreted.<ref>{{clarify span|References 4, 5 and 6|date=January 2018}}.</ref> The result can be:\n* {{kbd|\u22121}}: If the subtraction button {{keypress|\u2212}} is pressed after the multiplication {{keypress|\u00d7}}, it is interpreted as a correction of the {{keypress|\u00d7}} rather than a minus sign, so that 4&nbsp;\u2212&nbsp;5 is calculated.\n* {{kbd|20}}: If the change-sign button {{keypress|\u00b1}} is pressed before the 5, it isn't interpreted as \u22125, and 4\u202f\u00d7\u202f5 is calculated.\n* {{kbd|\u221220}}: To get the right answer, {{keypress|\u00b1}} must be pressed last, even though the minus sign isn't written last in the formula.<ref name=\"Reference 4\">{{clarify span|Reference 4|date=January 2018}}.</ref>\n\nThe effects of operator precedence, parentheses and non-commutative operators, on the sequence of button presses, are illustrated by:\n* {{kbd|4 \u2212 5\u202f\u00d7\u202f6}}: The multiplication must be done first, and the formula has to be rearranged and calculated as \u22125\u202f\u00d7\u202f6&nbsp;+&nbsp;4. So \u00b1 and addition have to be used rather than subtraction. When {{keypress|+}} is pressed, the multiplication is performed.\n* {{kbd|4\u202f\u00d7\u202f(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)}}: The addition must be done first, so the calculation carried out is (5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)\u202f\u00d7\u202f4. When {{keypress|\u00d7}} is pressed, the addition is performed.\n* {{kbd|4\u202f/\u202f(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)}}: One way to do this is to calculate (5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)\u202f/\u202f4 first and then use the {{keypress|1/''x''}} button, so the calculation carried out is 1/[(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)/4].\n* {{kbd|4\u202f\u00d7\u202f5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6\u202f\u00d7\u202f7}}: The two multiplications must be done before the addition, and one of the results must be put into memory.<ref name=\"Reference 4\"/>\n\nThese are only simple examples, but immediate-execution calculators can present even greater problems in more complex cases. In fact, Professor Thimbleby claims that users may have been conditioned to avoid them for all but the simplest calculations.<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}, section 3.2, second paragraph.</ref>\n\n===Declarative and imperative tools===\n\nThe potential problems with immediate-execution calculators stem from the fact that they are [[imperative programming|imperative]].<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}, sections 1 and 10.</ref> This means that the user must provide details of ''how'' the calculation has to be performed.\n\nProfessor Thimbleby has identified the need for a calculator that is more automatic and therefore easier to use, and he states that such a calculator should be more [[declarative programming|declarative]].<ref name=\"Reference 11\">{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}.</ref> This means that the user should be able to specify only ''what'' has to be done, not how, and in which order, it has to be done.\n\nFormula calculators are more declarative because the typed-in formula specifies what is to be done, and the user does not have to provide any details of the step-by-step order in which the calculation has to be performed.\n\nDeclarative solutions are easier to understand than imperative solutions,<ref name=\"Reference 11\"/><ref>{{cite web |author=Roy E. Furman |title=Declarative Programming \u2013 Strategies for Solving Software Problems |url=http://www.articlesalley.com/article.detail.php/7013/178/Education/Internet/36/Declarative_Programming_-_Strategies_for_Solving_Software_Problems |date=July 2006 |accessdate=2009-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120723100846/http://www.articlesalley.com/article.detail.php/7013/178/Education/Internet/36/Declarative_Programming_-_Strategies_for_Solving_Software_Problems |archivedate=2012-07-23 }}</ref> and there has been a long-term trend from imperative to declarative methods.<ref>David A. Watt. Programming language concepts and paradigms, Prentice Hall; 1990. Citation 13 at http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/context/14802/0.</ref><ref>Tatsuru Matsushita. Expressive Power of Declarative Programming Languages, PhD thesis, Department of Computer Science, University of York; October 1998. Citation 13 at http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/context/14802/0.</ref> Formula calculators are part of this trend.\n\nMany software tools for the general user, such as spreadsheets, are declarative.<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 20|date=January 2018}}, paragraph 6.</ref> Formula calculators are examples of such tools.\n\n===Using the full power of the computer===\n\nSoftware calculators that simulate hand-held, immediate execution calculators do not use the full power of the computer: \"A computer is a far more powerful device than a hand-held calculator, and thus it is illogical and limiting to duplicate hand-held calculators on a computer.\" (Haxial Software Pty Ltd)<ref>Reference 3, second paragraph</ref> Formula calculators use more of the computer's power because, besides calculating the value of a formula, they work out the order in which things should be done.\n\n=={{anchor|Algebraic|AESH|AESP|AOS|EOS}}Infix notation==\n[[File:Sharp Scientific Calculator.jpg|left|thumb|A Sharp scientific calculator using infix notation. Note the formula on the dot-matrix line above and the answer on the seven-segment line below, as well as the arrow keys allowing the entry to be reviewed and edited.]]\n{{redirect|Aesh|the letter|\u00c6}}\n\n[[File:Speedcrunch.png|thumb|right|This calculator program has accepted input in infix notation, and returned the answer <math>3\\text{,}8\\overline{6}</math>. Here the comma is a decimal separator.]]\n\n'''Infix notation''' is a method where unary operations are input into the calculator in the same order as they are written on paper. Different forms of this input scheme exist. In the '''algebraic entry system with hierarchy''' ('''AESH'''),<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> the precedence of basic mathematical operators is taken into account,<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> whereas calculators with '''algebraic entry system with parentheses''' ('''AESP''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> support the entry of parentheses.<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> An input scheme known as '''algebraic operating system''' ('''AOS''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> combines both.<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/>\n\nCalculators that use infix notation tend to incorporate a [[dot-matrix display]] to display the expression being entered, frequently accompanied by a seven-segment display for the result of the expression. Because the expression is not evaluated until it is fully entered, there is provision for editing the entered expression at any point prior to evaluation, as well as replaying entered expressions and their answers from memory.\n\nMost [[graphing calculators]] by [[Casio graphic calculators|Casio]] and [[Comparison of Texas Instruments graphing calculators|Texas Instruments]] use this method. On its [[scientific calculator]]s, [[Sharp Corporation|Sharp]] calls this method '''Direct Algebraic Logic (D.A.L.)''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://global.sharp/contents/calculator/features/standard/dal/index.html|title=SHARP|website=global.sharp}}</ref> and [[Casio]] calls this method the '''Visually Perfect Algebraic Method (V.P.A.M.)'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.casio.com/answer.php?rgn=5&cid=004002002001&qid=24370&num=7|title=General - Standard Scientific calculators - Calculators - CASIO|website=support.casio.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>(1 + 2) \\times (3 + 4)</math>\n| {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|4}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12\n|}\n\n=={{anchor|RPN}}Reverse Polish notation==\n[[File:Screenshot from 2015-09-10 21-56-23.png|thumb|right|Screenshot of an RPN Calculator program on [[Linux]].]]\n[[File:HP-10C programmable calculator.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Hewlett-Packard Voyager series]] of calculators all use RPN input. The \"Enter\" key is used here to push the value on the display onto the stack.]]\n{{main|Reverse Polish Notation}}\n\nIn '''reverse Polish notation''',<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> also known as '''postfix notation,''' all operations are entered after the [[operand]]s on which the operation is performed. Reverse Polish notation is parenthesis-free, which usually leads to fewer button presses needed to perform an operation. By the use of a [[Stack (data structure)|stack]], one can enter formulas without the need to rearrange operands.\n\n[[Hewlett-Packard]]'s [[HP calculators|calculators]] are well-known examples among calculators which use RPN. Early models, such as the [[HP-35]], used RPN entirely without any alternative methods. Later models, such as the [[HP 35s]], also had infix notation and could conveniently allow users to switch between it and RPN.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}  {{Keypress|+}}<br>\n{{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}}\n| 7<br>6\n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}\n| 7\n|-\n| <math>(1 + 2) \\times (3 + 4)</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|4}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}\n| 9\n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}}\n\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}}\n| 12<br>11 ([[Reverse Polish LISP|RPL]] and [[Entry RPN]])<ref name=\"RPN\"/><br>10 ([[Classical RPN]])<ref name=\"RPN\">http://h20331.www2.hp.com/hpsub/downloads/S07%20HP%20RPN%20Evolves%20V5b.pdf</ref>\n|}\n\nNote: The first example illustrates one of the few cases where reverse Polish notation does not use the fewest button presses &ndash; provided one does not rearrange operands. If one would do so then only six keystrokes would be needed.\n\n== {{anchor|RPN}}BASIC notation ==\n\n{{main|BASIC}}\n[[File:Heart-on-ti89-parametric.jpg|thumb|The equation entry screen on a [[TI-89 series|TI-89]], showing the brackets after the ln, sin and cos parameters. If these were left out, the equation would be interpreted as <math>\\ln(\\left\\vert t \\right\\vert+\\sin(t+\\cos(t)))</math> instead of <math>\\ln(\\left\\vert t \\right\\vert)+\\sin(t)+\\cos(t)</math>]]\n'''BASIC notation''' is a particular implementation of infix notation where functions require their [[function argument|parameters]] to be in brackets.\n\nThis method was used from the 1980s to the 1990s in BASIC programmable calculators and [[pocket computer]]s. Texas Instruments would later implement the method in many of its graphing calculators, including the [[TI-83 series|TI-83]] and [[TI-84 Plus series]]. Most [[computer algebra systems]] also use this as the default input method.\n\nIn BASIC notation, the formula is entered as it would be entered in [[BASIC]], using the <CODE>PRINT</CODE> command \u2013 the <CODE>PRINT</CODE> command itself being optional. On pressing \"ENTER\" or \"=\", the result would be displayed. As with standard infix notation, typing mistakes in the entered formula could be corrected using the same editor function as the one used when programming the calculator.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n\n{{Keypress|S}} {{Keypress|I}} {{Keypress|N}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|C}} {{Keypress|O}} {{Keypress|S}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 12\n\n16 \n|}\n\nFor the second example, two options are given depending on if the BASIC programmable pocket computers have dedicated trigonometric keys<ref>The picture of the [http://pocket.free.fr/html/casio/fx-880p_e.html Casio FX-880P] shows sin, cos and tan keys on the second row right hand side.</ref> or not.<ref>The picture of the [http://pocket.free.fr/html/sharp/pc-1245_e.html Sharp PC-1245] shows no trigonometric keys</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|RPN}}Ten key notation ==\n[[File:Sharp EL-1192D Calculator.jpg|thumb|This printing calculator made by Sharp uses ten-key notation. Notice the size and placement of the keys, including the extra-large \"+/=\" and the red \"-/=\" keys.]]\nThe '''ten-key notation''' input method first became popular with accountants' [[adding machine|paper tape adding machines]]. It generally makes the assumption that entered numbers are being summed, although other operations are supported. Each number entered is followed by its sign (+/\u2212), and a running total is kept. An assumption is made that the last operand can be implicitly used next, so by just entering another + (for example), one will reuse the most recent operand. Ten key input mode is available in printing calculators from companies such as [[Sharp Corporation|Sharp]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://siica.sharpusa.net/Business-Products/Calculators|title=SIICA.sharpusa.com > Resources > More Products > Calculators|website=siica.sharpusa.net}}</ref> and in software calculators like Judy's TenKey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judysapps.com/TenKey.htm|title=Award-Winning Judy's TenKey Accounting Calculator for Windows|website=www.judysapps.com}}</ref> used by accounting firms. Online tenkey training and certification tools are available as well,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learn2type.com/typingtest/tenkeycertificate.cfm|title=Ten Key Certificate on Learn2Type.com!|website=Learn2Type.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.abbyinc.com/abbyinc/KeyPro.asp</ref> and some businesses use [[words per minute#Numeric entry|ten key typing speed]] as an employment criterion.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|T}} \n| 8 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>5-3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|-}} {{Keypress|T}}\n| 5 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|T}}\n| 9\n|}\n\n=={{anchor|Textbook}}Mathematical display==\n\n[[File:CalculatorFractions-5550x.jpg|thumb|200x200px|A Casio ''Natural Display'' scientific calculator displaying mixed fractions and their decimal equivalents in pretty-printing.]]{{See also|Prettyprint}}\n[[File:Mathematica dinis surface.png|left|thumb|Pretty-printed commands used to plot [[Dini's surface]] in Mathematica.]]\nModern computer algebra systems, as well as many scientific and graphing calculators, allow for \"'''pretty-printing'''\", that is, entry of equations such that [[Fraction (mathematics)|fractions]], [[Nth root#Working with surds|surds]] and [[integral]]s, etc. are displayed in the way they would normally be written. Such calculators are generally similar in appearance to those using infix notation, but feature a full dot-matrix display and templates for entering expressions, which are navigated using arrow keys on the calculator. The templates contain spaces for values or expressions to be entered, and empty values would typically result in a syntax error, making it more cumbersome to navigate than standard infix notation; standard infix notation is often an option on such calculators as well.\n\nCasio used to call this feature ''Natural Display'' or ''Natural textbook display'',<ref>[http://edu.casio.com/products/ntd/fx991es/ Natural textbook display - Scientific calculator].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edu.casio.com/|title=CASIO WEW Worldwide Education Website|website=CASIO WEW Worldwide Education Website}}</ref> but now uses ''Natural-VPAM''.<ref>[http://edu.casio.com/products/adves/fx991esplus/ Natural Visually Perfect Algebraic Mode (V.P.A.M) - Scientific calculator] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427153102/http://edu.casio.com/products/adves/fx991esplus/ |date=27 April 2009 }}.</ref> Sharp calls this ''WriteView''<ref>[http://sharp-world.com/contents/calculator/features/standard/writeview/index.html WriteView].</ref> on its scientific calculators and simply ''Equation Editor'' on its graphing calculators.<ref>[http://sharp-world.com/contents/calculator/features/graphing/eq/index.html Sharp Graphing equation editor].</ref> HP calls this its ''Textbook'' display setting,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://h20564.www2.hp.com/hpsc/doc/public/display?docId=emr_na-c01943918|title=HP Support document - HP Support Center|last=Inc.|first=HP|website=h20564.www2.hp.com|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> which can be used in both RPN and Algebraic mode and in both the ''Stack'' and in the ''Equation Writer'' application.<ref>http://h20331.www2.hp.com/Hpsub/downloads/50gUsing_the_EquationWriter_Part2.pdf.</ref> [[Mathematica]] calls this ''Semantic-Faithful Typesetting''.<ref>[http://www.wolfram.com/technology/guide/SemanticFaithfulTypesetting/ Semantic-Faithful Typesetting].</ref> [[Mathcad]] calls this ''standard math notation''.<ref>[http://www.ptc.com/WCMS/files/56916/en/3549_Mathcad_bro_ViewONLY.pdf Mathcad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920223357/http://www.ptc.com/WCMS/files/56916/en/3549_Mathcad_bro_ViewONLY.pdf |date=20 September 2008 }}.</ref> [[Maple (software)|Maple]] has a ''Math Equation Editor'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maplesoft.com/products/maple/features/feature_detail.aspx?fid=5907|title=Math Equation Editor - Maple Features - Maplesoft|website=www.maplesoft.com}}</ref> but does not have a special name for this input method. Texas Instruments calls it ''MathPrint,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.ti.com/en/products|title=TI Products &#124; Graphing Calculators &#124; Scientific Calculators|website=education.ti.com}}</ref> incorporating it in its high-end calculators, such as the [[TI-Nspire series]], and in 2011 added the feature to its TI-84 series with the 2.55 OS update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techpoweredmath.com/new-os-ti-84-255-mp/|title=Texas Instruments releases new OS for TI-84, 2.55 MP|date=2011-01-14|website=Tech Powered Math|language=en-us|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|\u2192}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}}  {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n\n{{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|(}}  {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 9\n12\n|-\n| <math>5-3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|\u2212}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 4 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 12\n|}\n\nFor the second example, two options are given, depending on whether the calculators will automatically insert needed parentheses or not. Machines equipped with an alphanumeric display will display <tt>SIN(30)\u00d7COS(30)</tt> before {{Keypress|ENTER}} is pressed.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Calculator]]\n* [[Comparison of software calculators]]\n* [[Computer algebra system]]\n* [[Graphing calculator]]\n* [[Keystroke programming]]\n* [[Mathematical notation]]\n* [[Pocket computer]]\n* [[Programmable calculator]]\n* [[Scientific calculator]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calculator Input Methods}}\n[[Category:Calculators]]\n[[Category:Mathematical notation]]\n", "text_old": "{{Original research|date=May 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019|cs1-dates=y}}\nThere are various ways in which [[calculator]]s interpret keystrokes. These can be categorized into two main types:\n\n* On a '''single-step''' or '''immediate-execution calculator''', the user presses a key for each operation, calculating all the intermediate results, before the final value is shown.<ref>Microsoft\u2019s Windows Operating System Calculator Accessory; 2001. Available on a Windows PC at: Start/All Programs/Accessories/Calculator.</ref><ref>MotionNET [http://www.motionnet.com/calculator Calculator page on the Internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501082324/http://www.motionnet.com/calculator/ |date=1 May 2009 }}; 2006.</ref><ref>Flow Simulation Ltd [http://www.calculator.org/jcalc98.html Virtual Calc98 page on the Internet]; 2008.</ref>\n* On an '''expression''' or '''formula calculator''', one types in an expression and then presses a key, such as \"=\" or \"Enter\", to evaluate the expression.<ref>Formula Calculators Pty Ltd [Home page on the Internet]; 2009.</ref><ref>Moisey Oysgelt [http://www.alemoi.com/math JavaScript Formula Calculator page on the Internet]; 2000.</ref><ref>Haxial Software Pty Ltd [http://www.haxial.com/products/calculator Calculator Product page on the Internet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090428221125/http://www.haxial.com/products/calculator/ |date=28 April 2009 }}; 2001</ref> There are various systems for typing in an expression, as described below.\n\n=={{anchor|Chain|AES}}Immediate execution==\n[[File:TI-108.jpg|thumb|208x208px|The [[TI-108]] is a simple four-function calculator which uses single-step execution.]]\nThe '''immediate execution''' mode of operation (also known as '''single-step''', '''algebraic entry system''' ('''AES''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\">{{cite book |title=Algorithms for RPN calculators |url=https://archive.org/details/algorithmsforrpn0000ball |url-access=registration |first=John A. |last=Ball |date=1978 |edition=1 |publisher=[[Wiley-Interscience]], [[John Wiley & Sons, Inc.]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA |isbn=0-471-03070-8}}</ref> or '''chain calculation''' mode) is commonly employed on most general-purpose calculators. In most simple four-function calculators, such as the [[Windows Calculator|Windows calculator]] in Standard mode and those included with most early [[Operating system|operating systems]], each [[binary operation]] is executed as soon as the next operator is pressed, and therefore the [[order of operations]] in a mathematical expression is not taken into account. [[Scientific calculators]], including the Scientific mode in the Windows calculator and most modern software calculators, have buttons for brackets and ''can'' take order of operation into account. Also, for [[unary operation]]s, like \u221a or ''x''<sup>2</sup>, the number is entered first, then the operator; this is largely because the display screens on these kinds of calculators are generally composed entirely of [[Seven-segment display|seven-segment characters]] and thus capable  of displaying only numbers, not the functions associated with them. This mode of operation also makes it impossible to change the expression being input without clearing the display entirely.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 7\n\n7\n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n\n{{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|x}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}}{{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>5 - 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|\u2212}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 4 \n|-\n| <math>15 + 10 + 10 + 10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12\n|}\n\nThe first and second example have been given twice. The first version is for simple calculators, showing how it is necessary to rearrange operands in order to get the correct result. The second version is for [[scientific calculator|scientific calculators]], where operator precedence is observed.\n\nImmediate-execution calculators are based on a mixture of infix and postfix notation: binary operations are done as infix, but unary operations are postfix. Because operators are applied one-at-a-time, the user must work out which operator key to use at each stage, and this can lead to problems.<ref>{{cite web |author=Harold Thimbleby |url=http://www.uclic.ucl.ac.uk/harold/srf/allcalcs.pdf |title=A new calculator and why it is necessary |publisher=Computing Science, Middlesex University, London, UK |date=September 1998 |accessdate=2009-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207044654/http://www.uclic.ucl.ac.uk/harold/srf/allcalcs.pdf |archivedate=2007-02-07 }}</ref><ref>Neville Holmes. [http://standards.computer.org/sabminutes/2003Wint/Truth%20and%20Clarity%20in%20Arithmetic%20-%20Neville%20Holmes.pdf Truth and Clarity in Arithmetic] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007234721/http://standards.computer.org/sabminutes/2003Wint/Truth%20and%20Clarity%20in%20Arithmetic%20-%20Neville%20Holmes.pdf |date=7 October 2006 }}, University of Tasmania; 2003.</ref> When discussing these problems, Professor [[Harold Thimbleby]] has pointed out that button-operated calculators \"require numbers and operation signs to be punched in a certain order, and mistakes are easy to make and hard to spot\".<ref>[http://www.physorg.com/news4773.html Professor devises easier calculator]; www.physorg.com. June 2005.</ref>\n\nProblems can occur because, for anything but the simplest calculation, in order to work out the value of a written formula, the user of a button-operated calculator is required to:\n* Rearrange the formula so that the value can be calculated by pressing buttons one at a time, while taking operator precedence and parentheses into account.\n* Use memory buttons to ensure that operations are applied in the correct order.\n* Use the special buttons {{keypress|\u00b1}} and {{keypress|1/''x''}}, that do not correspond to operations in the formula, for non-commutative operators.\n\nMistakes can be hard to spot because:\n* For the above reasons, the sequence of button presses may bear little resemblance to the original formula.\n* The operation carried out when a button is pressed is not always the same as the button, but could be a previously entered operation.\n\n[[File:Calculator-TI-30XA-rev2015.jpg|thumb|This TI-30XA scientific calculator uses immediate execution. It has a one-line, seven-segmented display, and cannot display operands or allow the entries to be edited.]]\n\n===Examples of difficulties===\n\nThe simplest example given by Professor Thimbleby of a possible problem when using an immediate-execution calculator is 4\u202f\u00d7\u202f(\u22125).<ref>Reference 11, section 2.</ref> As a written formula the value of this is \u221220 because the minus sign is intended to indicate a negative number, rather than a subtraction, and this is the way that it would be interpreted by a formula calculator.\n\nOn an immediate-execution calculator, depending on which keys are used and the order in which they are pressed, the result for this calculation may be different. Also there are differences between calculators in the way a given sequence of button presses is interpreted.<ref>{{clarify span|References 4, 5 and 6|date=January 2018}}.</ref> The result can be:\n* {{kbd|\u22121}}: If the subtraction button {{keypress|\u2212}} is pressed after the multiplication {{keypress|\u00d7}}, it is interpreted as a correction of the {{keypress|\u00d7}} rather than a minus sign, so that 4&nbsp;\u2212&nbsp;5 is calculated.\n* {{kbd|20}}: If the change-sign button {{keypress|\u00b1}} is pressed before the 5, it isn't interpreted as \u22125, and 4\u202f\u00d7\u202f5 is calculated.\n* {{kbd|\u221220}}: To get the right answer, {{keypress|\u00b1}} must be pressed last, even though the minus sign isn't written last in the formula.<ref name=\"Reference 4\">{{clarify span|Reference 4|date=January 2018}}.</ref>\n\nThe effects of operator precedence, parentheses and non-commutative operators, on the sequence of button presses, are illustrated by:\n* {{kbd|4 \u2212 5\u202f\u00d7\u202f6}}: The multiplication must be done first, and the formula has to be rearranged and calculated as \u22125\u202f\u00d7\u202f6&nbsp;+&nbsp;4. So \u00b1 and addition have to be used rather than subtraction. When {{keypress|+}} is pressed, the multiplication is performed.\n* {{kbd|4\u202f\u00d7\u202f(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)}}: The addition must be done first, so the calculation carried out is (5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)\u202f\u00d7\u202f4. When {{keypress|\u00d7}} is pressed, the addition is performed.\n* {{kbd|4\u202f/\u202f(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)}}: One way to do this is to calculate (5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)\u202f/\u202f4 first and then use the {{keypress|1/''x''}} button, so the calculation carried out is 1/[(5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6)/4].\n* {{kbd|4\u202f\u00d7\u202f5&nbsp;+&nbsp;6\u202f\u00d7\u202f7}}: The two multiplications must be done before the addition, and one of the results must be put into memory.<ref name=\"Reference 4\"/>\n\nThese are only simple examples, but immediate-execution calculators can present even greater problems in more complex cases. In fact, Professor Thimbleby claims that users may have been conditioned to avoid them for all but the simplest calculations.<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}, section 3.2, second paragraph.</ref>\n\n===Declarative and imperative tools===\n\nThe potential problems with immediate-execution calculators stem from the fact that they are [[imperative programming|imperative]].<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}, sections 1 and 10.</ref> This means that the user must provide details of ''how'' the calculation has to be performed.\n\nProfessor Thimbleby has identified the need for a calculator that is more automatic and therefore easier to use, and he states that such a calculator should be more [[declarative programming|declarative]].<ref name=\"Reference 11\">{{clarify span|Reference 11|date=January 2018}}.</ref> This means that the user should be able to specify only ''what'' has to be done, not how, and in which order, it has to be done.\n\nFormula calculators are more declarative because the typed-in formula specifies what is to be done, and the user does not have to provide any details of the step-by-step order in which the calculation has to be performed.\n\nDeclarative solutions are easier to understand than imperative solutions,<ref name=\"Reference 11\"/><ref>{{cite web |author=Roy E. Furman |title=Declarative Programming \u2013 Strategies for Solving Software Problems |url=http://www.articlesalley.com/article.detail.php/7013/178/Education/Internet/36/Declarative_Programming_-_Strategies_for_Solving_Software_Problems |date=July 2006 |accessdate=2009-05-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120723100846/http://www.articlesalley.com/article.detail.php/7013/178/Education/Internet/36/Declarative_Programming_-_Strategies_for_Solving_Software_Problems |archivedate=2012-07-23 }}</ref> and there has been a long-term trend from imperative to declarative methods.<ref>David A. Watt. Programming language concepts and paradigms, Prentice Hall; 1990. Citation 13 at http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/context/14802/0.</ref><ref>Tatsuru Matsushita. Expressive Power of Declarative Programming Languages, PhD thesis, Department of Computer Science, University of York; October 1998. Citation 13 at http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/context/14802/0.</ref> Formula calculators are part of this trend.\n\nMany software tools for the general user, such as spreadsheets, are declarative.<ref>{{clarify span|Reference 20|date=January 2018}}, paragraph 6.</ref> Formula calculators are examples of such tools.\n\n===Using the full power of the computer===\n\nSoftware calculators that simulate hand-held, immediate execution calculators do not use the full power of the computer: \"A computer is a far more powerful device than a hand-held calculator, and thus it is illogical and limiting to duplicate hand-held calculators on a computer.\" (Haxial Software Pty Ltd)<ref>Reference 3, second paragraph</ref> Formula calculators use more of the computer's power because, besides calculating the value of a formula, they work out the order in which things should be done.\n\n=={{anchor|Algebraic|AESH|AESP|AOS|EOS}}Infix notation==\n[[File:Sharp Scientific Calculator.jpg|left|thumb|A Sharp scientific calculator using infix notation. Note the formula on the dot-matrix line above and the answer on the seven-segment line below, as well as the arrow keys allowing the entry to be reviewed and edited.]]\n{{redirect|Aesh|the letter|\u00c6}}\n\n[[File:Speedcrunch.png|thumb|right|This calculator program has accepted input in infix notation, and returned the answer <math>3\\text{,}8\\overline{6}</math>. Here the comma is a decimal separator.]]\n\n'''Infix notation''' is a method where unary operations are input into the calculator in the same order as they are written on paper. Different forms of this input scheme exist. In the '''algebraic entry system with hierarchy''' ('''AESH'''),<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> the precedence of basic mathematical operators is taken into account,<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> whereas calculators with '''algebraic entry system with parentheses''' ('''AESP''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> support the entry of parentheses.<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> An input scheme known as '''algebraic operating system''' ('''AOS''')<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> combines both.<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/>\n\nCalculators that use infix notation tend to incorporate a [[dot-matrix display]] to display the expression being entered, frequently accompanied by a seven-segment display for the result of the expression. Because the expression is not evaluated until it is fully entered, there is provision for editing the entered expression at any point prior to evaluation, as well as replaying entered expressions and their answers from memory.\n\nMost [[graphing calculators]] by [[Casio graphic calculators|Casio]] and [[Comparison of Texas Instruments graphing calculators|Texas Instruments]] use this method. On its [[scientific calculator]]s, [[Sharp Corporation|Sharp]] calls this method '''Direct Algebraic Logic (D.A.L.)''',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://global.sharp/contents/calculator/features/standard/dal/index.html|title=SHARP|website=global.sharp}}</ref> and [[Casio]] calls this method the '''Visually Perfect Algebraic Method (V.P.A.M.)'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.casio.com/answer.php?rgn=5&cid=004002002001&qid=24370&num=7|title=General - Standard Scientific calculators - Calculators - CASIO|website=support.casio.com}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>(1 + 2) \\times (3 + 4)</math>\n| {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|4}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 12\n|}\n\n=={{anchor|RPN}}Reverse Polish notation==\n[[File:Screenshot from 2015-09-10 21-56-23.png|thumb|right|Screenshot of an RPN Calculator program on [[Linux]].]]\n[[File:HP-10C programmable calculator.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Hewlett-Packard Voyager series]] of calculators all use RPN input. The \"Enter\" key is used here to push the value on the display onto the stack.]]\n{{main|Reverse Polish Notation}}\n\nIn '''reverse Polish notation''',<ref name=\"Ball_1978\"/> also known as '''postfix notation,''' all operations are entered after the [[operand]]s on which the operation is performed. Reverse Polish notation is parenthesis-free, which usually leads to fewer button presses needed to perform an operation. By the use of a [[Stack (data structure)|stack]], one can enter formulas without the need to rearrange operands.\n\n[[Hewlett-Packard]]'s [[HP calculators|calculators]] are well-known examples among calculators which use RPN. Early models, such as the [[HP-35]], used RPN entirely without any alternative methods. Later models, such as the [[HP 35s]], also had infix notation and could conveniently allow users to switch between it and RPN.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}  {{Keypress|+}}<br>\n{{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}}\n| 7<br>6\n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}\n| 7\n|-\n| <math>(1 + 2) \\times (3 + 4)</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|4}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}}\n| 9\n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|ENTER}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}}\n\n{{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}} {{Keypress|ENTER^}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}}\n| 12<br>11 ([[Reverse Polish LISP|RPL]] and [[Entry RPN]])<ref name=\"RPN\"/><br>10 ([[Classical RPN]])<ref name=\"RPN\">http://h20331.www2.hp.com/hpsub/downloads/S07%20HP%20RPN%20Evolves%20V5b.pdf</ref>\n|}\n\nNote: The first example illustrates one of the few cases where reverse Polish notation does not use the fewest button presses &ndash; provided one does not rearrange operands. If one would do so then only six keystrokes would be needed.\n\n== {{anchor|RPN}}BASIC notation ==\n\n{{main|BASIC}}\n[[File:Heart-on-ti89-parametric.jpg|thumb|The equation entry screen on a [[TI-89 series|TI-89]], showing the brackets after the ln, sin and cos parameters. If these were left out, the equation would be interpreted as <math>\\ln(\\left\\vert t \\right\\vert+\\sin(t+\\cos(t)))</math> instead of <math>\\ln(\\left\\vert t \\right\\vert)+\\sin(t)+\\cos(t)</math>]]\n'''BASIC notation''' is a particular implementation of infix notation where functions require their [[function argument|parameters]] to be in brackets.\n\nThis method was used from the 1980s to the 1990s in BASIC programmable calculators and [[pocket computer]]s. Texas Instruments would later implement the method in many of its graphing calculators, including the [[TI-83 series|TI-83]] and [[TI-84 Plus series]]. Most [[computer algebra systems]] also use this as the default input method.\n\nIn BASIC notation, the formula is entered as it would be entered in [[BASIC]], using the <CODE>PRINT</CODE> command \u2013 the <CODE>PRINT</CODE> command itself being optional. On pressing \"ENTER\" or \"=\", the result would be displayed. As with standard infix notation, typing mistakes in the entered formula could be corrected using the same editor function as the one used when programming the calculator.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n\n{{Keypress|S}} {{Keypress|I}} {{Keypress|N}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|C}} {{Keypress|O}} {{Keypress|S}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 12\n\n16 \n|}\n\nFor the second example, two options are given depending on if the BASIC programmable pocket computers have dedicated trigonometric keys<ref>The picture of the [http://pocket.free.fr/html/casio/fx-880p_e.html Casio FX-880P] shows sin, cos and tan keys on the second row right hand side.</ref> or not.<ref>The picture of the [http://pocket.free.fr/html/sharp/pc-1245_e.html Sharp PC-1245] shows no trigonometric keys</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|RPN}}Ten key notation ==\n[[File:Sharp Calculator.JPG|thumb|This printing calculator made by Sharp uses ten-key notation. Notice the size and placement of the keys, including the extra-large \"+/=\" and the red \"-/=\" keys.]]\nThe '''ten-key notation''' input method first became popular with accountants' [[adding machine|paper tape adding machines]]. It generally makes the assumption that entered numbers are being summed, although other operations are supported. Each number entered is followed by its sign (+/\u2212), and a running total is kept. An assumption is made that the last operand can be implicitly used next, so by just entering another + (for example), one will reuse the most recent operand. Ten key input mode is available in printing calculators from companies such as [[Sharp Corporation|Sharp]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://siica.sharpusa.net/Business-Products/Calculators|title=SIICA.sharpusa.com > Resources > More Products > Calculators|website=siica.sharpusa.net}}</ref> and in software calculators like Judy's TenKey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judysapps.com/TenKey.htm|title=Award-Winning Judy's TenKey Accounting Calculator for Windows|website=www.judysapps.com}}</ref> used by accounting firms. Online tenkey training and certification tools are available as well,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learn2type.com/typingtest/tenkeycertificate.cfm|title=Ten Key Certificate on Learn2Type.com!|website=Learn2Type.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.abbyinc.com/abbyinc/KeyPro.asp</ref> and some businesses use [[words per minute#Numeric entry|ten key typing speed]] as an employment criterion.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|1==}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|T}} \n| 8 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|1==}}\n| 8\n|-\n| <math>5-3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|-}} {{Keypress|T}}\n| 5 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|T}}\n| 9\n|}\n\n=={{anchor|Textbook}}Mathematical display==\n\n[[File:CalculatorFractions-5550x.jpg|thumb|200x200px|A Casio ''Natural Display'' scientific calculator displaying mixed fractions and their decimal equivalents in pretty-printing.]]{{See also|Prettyprint}}\n[[File:Mathematica dinis surface.png|left|thumb|Pretty-printed commands used to plot [[Dini's surface]] in Mathematica.]]\nModern computer algebra systems, as well as many scientific and graphing calculators, allow for \"'''pretty-printing'''\", that is, entry of equations such that [[Fraction (mathematics)|fractions]], [[Nth root#Working with surds|surds]] and [[integral]]s, etc. are displayed in the way they would normally be written. Such calculators are generally similar in appearance to those using infix notation, but feature a full dot-matrix display and templates for entering expressions, which are navigated using arrow keys on the calculator. The templates contain spaces for values or expressions to be entered, and empty values would typically result in a syntax error, making it more cumbersome to navigate than standard infix notation; standard infix notation is often an option on such calculators as well.\n\nCasio used to call this feature ''Natural Display'' or ''Natural textbook display'',<ref>[http://edu.casio.com/products/ntd/fx991es/ Natural textbook display - Scientific calculator].</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edu.casio.com/|title=CASIO WEW Worldwide Education Website|website=CASIO WEW Worldwide Education Website}}</ref> but now uses ''Natural-VPAM''.<ref>[http://edu.casio.com/products/adves/fx991esplus/ Natural Visually Perfect Algebraic Mode (V.P.A.M) - Scientific calculator] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090427153102/http://edu.casio.com/products/adves/fx991esplus/ |date=27 April 2009 }}.</ref> Sharp calls this ''WriteView''<ref>[http://sharp-world.com/contents/calculator/features/standard/writeview/index.html WriteView].</ref> on its scientific calculators and simply ''Equation Editor'' on its graphing calculators.<ref>[http://sharp-world.com/contents/calculator/features/graphing/eq/index.html Sharp Graphing equation editor].</ref> HP calls this its ''Textbook'' display setting,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://h20564.www2.hp.com/hpsc/doc/public/display?docId=emr_na-c01943918|title=HP Support document - HP Support Center|last=Inc.|first=HP|website=h20564.www2.hp.com|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref> which can be used in both RPN and Algebraic mode and in both the ''Stack'' and in the ''Equation Writer'' application.<ref>http://h20331.www2.hp.com/Hpsub/downloads/50gUsing_the_EquationWriter_Part2.pdf.</ref> [[Mathematica]] calls this ''Semantic-Faithful Typesetting''.<ref>[http://www.wolfram.com/technology/guide/SemanticFaithfulTypesetting/ Semantic-Faithful Typesetting].</ref> [[Mathcad]] calls this ''standard math notation''.<ref>[http://www.ptc.com/WCMS/files/56916/en/3549_Mathcad_bro_ViewONLY.pdf Mathcad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080920223357/http://www.ptc.com/WCMS/files/56916/en/3549_Mathcad_bro_ViewONLY.pdf |date=20 September 2008 }}.</ref> [[Maple (software)|Maple]] has a ''Math Equation Editor'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maplesoft.com/products/maple/features/feature_detail.aspx?fid=5907|title=Math Equation Editor - Maple Features - Maplesoft|website=www.maplesoft.com}}</ref> but does not have a special name for this input method. Texas Instruments calls it ''MathPrint,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://education.ti.com/en/products|title=TI Products &#124; Graphing Calculators &#124; Scientific Calculators|website=education.ti.com}}</ref> incorporating it in its high-end calculators, such as the [[TI-Nspire series]], and in 2011 added the feature to its TI-84 series with the 2.55 OS update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techpoweredmath.com/new-os-ti-84-255-mp/|title=Texas Instruments releases new OS for TI-84, 2.55 MP|date=2011-01-14|website=Tech Powered Math|language=en-us|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|+ Examples\n! Formula\n! keystrokes\n! keystroke count\n|-\n| <math>1 + 2 \\times 3</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|+}} {{Keypress|2}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 6 \n|-\n| <math>\\sin 30 \\times \\cos 30</math>\n| {{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|\u2192}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}}  {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n\n{{Keypress|SIN}} {{Keypress|(}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|\u00d7}} {{Keypress|COS}} {{Keypress|(}}  {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|)}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 9\n12\n|-\n| <math>5-3</math>\n| {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|\u2212}} {{Keypress|3}} {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 4 \n|-\n| <math>15+10+10+10</math>\n| {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|5}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}} {{Keypress|+}}  {{Keypress|1}} {{Keypress|0}}  {{Keypress|ENTER}}\n| 12\n|}\n\nFor the second example, two options are given, depending on whether the calculators will automatically insert needed parentheses or not. Machines equipped with an alphanumeric display will display <tt>SIN(30)\u00d7COS(30)</tt> before {{Keypress|ENTER}} is pressed.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Calculator]]\n* [[Comparison of software calculators]]\n* [[Computer algebra system]]\n* [[Graphing calculator]]\n* [[Keystroke programming]]\n* [[Mathematical notation]]\n* [[Pocket computer]]\n* [[Programmable calculator]]\n* [[Scientific calculator]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calculator Input Methods}}\n[[Category:Calculators]]\n[[Category:Mathematical notation]]\n", "name_user": "Crookesmoor", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Sharp Calculator.JPG\u2192File:Sharp EL-1192D Calculator.jpg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculator_input_methods"}
{"title_page": "Clive McFadzean", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Clive McFadzean\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Clive Stuart McFadzean<ref name = \"Hugman\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1958|3|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Kilmarnock]], Scotland\n|height      = \n|position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|youthyears1 = \n|youthclubs1 = [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]]\n|youthyears2 = 1974\u20131976\n|youthclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n|years1      = 1976\u20131977\n|clubs1      = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|caps1       = 4\n|goals1      = 2\n|years2      = \n|clubs2      = Ossett\n|caps2       = \n|goals2      =\n|totalcaps   = \n|totalgoals  = \n}}\n'''Clive Stuart McFadzean''' (born 11 March 1958) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Kilmarnock]],<ref name = \"Hugman\">{{Hugman|12443|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref> McFadzean joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] from [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]] in November 1974.<ref name = \"F401\">Frost, p. 401</ref> He joined the first-team in March 1976,<ref name = \"Hugman\"/> making four league appearances for the club, scoring two goals.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/><ref>Frost, p. 385</ref><ref name = \"NB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/bradfordcity/bradfordcity.html|title=\nBRADFORD CITY : 1946/47 - 2013/14|accessdate=3 November 2018|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database}}</ref> He was released by the club in 1977,<ref name = \"F401\"/> later playing for Ossett.<ref name = \"NB\"/>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Frost|first=Terry|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988|publisher=Breedon Books Sport|year=1988|isbn=0-907969-38-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadzean, Clive}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Farsley Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name        = Clive McFadzean\n|image       = \n|image_size  = \n|caption     = \n|fullname    = Clive Stuart McFadzean<ref name = \"Hugman\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1958|3|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Kilmarnock]], Scotland\n|height      = \n|position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n|youthyears1 = \n|youthclubs1 = [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]]\n|youthyears2 = 1974\u20131976\n|youthclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] \n|years1      = 1976\u20131977\n|clubs1      = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n|caps1       = 4\n|goals1      = 2\n|years2      = \n|clubs2      = Ossett\n|caps2       = \n|goals2      =\n|totalcaps   = \n|totalgoals  = \n}}\n'''Clive Stuart McFadzean''' (born 11 March 1958) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Kilmarnock]],<ref name = \"Hugman\">{{Hugman|12443|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref> McFadzean joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] from [[Farsley Celtic F.C.|Farsley Celtic]] in November 1974.<ref name = \"F401\">Frost, p. 401</ref> He joined the first-team in March 1976,<ref name = \"Hugman\"/> making four league appearances for the club, scoring two goals.<ref name = \"Hugman\"/><ref>Frost, p. 385</ref><ref name = \"NB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/bradfordcity/bradfordcity.html|title=\nBRADFORD CITY : 1946/47 - 2013/14|accessdate=3 November 2018|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database}}</ref> He was released by the club in 1977,<ref name = \"F401\"/> later playing for Ossett.<ref name = \"NB\"/>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Frost|first=Terry|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903-1988|publisher=Breedon Books Sport|year=1988|isbn=0-907969-38-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFadzean, Clive}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Farsley Celtic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n\n{{Scotland-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clive_McFadzean"}
{"title_page": "Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox song contest national year \n| Year                  = 2012\n| Country                = Portugal\n| Preselection           = Festival Da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012\n| Preselection date      = 10 March 2012\n| Entrant                = [[Filipa Sousa]]\n| Song                   = [[Vida minha]]\n| SF result              = ''Failed to qualify'' (13th, 39 points)\n| Prev                   = 2011\n| Next                   = 2014\n}}\n'''Portugal''' participated in the '''Eurovision Song Contest 2012''' in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]]. The Portuguese entry was selected through Festival Da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012,  a national final organised by the Portuguese broadcaster [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]. [[Filipa Sousa]] represented Portugal with the song \"[[Vida minha]]\", which failed to qualify from the second semi-final, achieving 13th place with 39 points.<ref name=semi2results>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2012 Semi-Final (2)|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1583#Scoreboard|work=Eurovision.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Victor M.|last=Escuerdo|title=Filipa Sousa for Portugal in Baku|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=48813&_t=filipa_sousa_for_portugal_in_baku|work=Eurovision.tv|date=11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nPortugal was considered to withdraw, because of the economic crisis in the country, but on 30 November 2011, RTP confirmed its participation in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012 in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]].<ref name=\"Portugal1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/11/25/portugal-decides-on-march-10/|title=Portugal decides on March 10th|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=25 November 2011|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129032047/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/11/25/portugal-decides-on-march-10/|archivedate=29 November 2011|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Before Eurovision ==\n\n=== Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012 ===\n''Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012'' was the 48th edition of [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o]], the music competition that selects Portugal's entries for the Eurovision Song Contest.\n\n==== Competing entries ====\nArtists were able to submit their applications through the RTP official website before 31 December 2011. Applicants then advanced to the auditions that were held in [[Lisbon]] (5 and 6 January 2012) and [[Oporto]] (10 and 11 January 2012), where they had to sing in Portuguese or in a foreign language (e.g. English). An exception was made for applications from established artists, which they can directly send in their songs to RTP without having to go through the auditions. RTS received more than 400 applications, and a jury chose 12 candidates and 5 back-ups to compete in the national final, which were revealed on 13 January 2012.<ref name=\"Portugal3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/02/rtp-receives-more-than-400-applications/|title=RTP receives more than 400 applications|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=2 January 2012|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112052527/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/02/rtp-receives-more-than-400-applications/|archivedate=12 January 2012|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Three of the final twelve artists: Carlos Costa, Ricardo Soler and Rui Andrade didn't go through the auditions, using instead their recognition as moderate established artists. Soler competed in the [[Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]] edition of Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o, finishing fourth, while Andrade finished third in the [[Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]] edition.<ref name=\"Portugal4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/13/rtp-announces-the-national-finalists//|title=Portugal: RTP announces 2012 national finalists|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=13 January 2012|publisher=oikotimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nRTP then directly invited six composers from various musical styles to compose songs for the selected artists. Composers and authors will create new songs specially for the 12 candidates, in order to suit their vocal skills. The songs must be no longer than three minutes, and had to be performed in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]. Two music producers were also invited by RTP to work in coordination with the composers in produce the 12 entries.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! Artist\n! Song\n! Lyrics (l) / Music (m)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Arm\u00e9nio Pimenta\n| align=\"left\" |\"Um poema na bagagem\"\n| align=\"left\" |Menito Ramos (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Carlos Costa\n| align=\"left\" |\"Queres que eu dance?\"\n| align=\"left\" |Jo\u00e3o S\u00f3 (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |C\u00famplices\n| align=\"left\" |\"Ser\u00e1 o que ser\u00e1\"\n| align=\"left\" |Jony Galv\u00e3o, Rui Reis (m&l)\n|- bgcolor=\"gold\"\n| align=\"left\" |'''[[Filipa Sousa]]'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''\"[[Vida minha]]\"'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''[[Andrej Babi\u0107]] (m), Carlos Coelho (l)'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Gerson Santos\n| align=\"left\" |\"Redescobrir Portugal\"\n| align=\"left\" |T\u00f3 Z\u00e9 (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Joana Leite\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor \u00e9 maior que a vida\"\n| align=\"left\" |Tiago Dias (m), Marisa Liz(l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Pamela Salvado\n| align=\"left\" |\"Fica a saudade\"\n| align=\"left\" |[[Miguel Gameiro]] (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Pedro Macedo\n| align=\"left\" |\"Outono em forma de gente\"\n| align=\"left\" |Pedro Marques (m&l), [[Daniela Varela]] (m&l), Jaime Oliveira  (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Ricardo Soler\n| align=\"left\" |\"Gratia plena\"\n| align=\"left\" |Nuno Feist (m), Nuno Silva (l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Rui Andrade\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor a preto e branco\"\n| align=\"left\" |Miguel Majer (m&l), In\u00eas Vaz (l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |T\u00f3 Martins\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amanh\u00e3 come\u00e7a o meu futuro\"\n| align=\"left\" |Toz\u00e9 Brito (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |V\u00e2nia Os\u00f3rio\n| align=\"left\" |\"O mundo passa\"\n| align=\"left\" |Armando Teixeira (m&l)\n|- \n|}\n==== Final ====\nThe final was held on 10 March 2012, hosted by [[S\u00edlvia Alberto]] and Pedro Granger.<ref name=\"Portugal5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/30/rtp-annouces-hosts-to-festival-da-cancao///|title=Portugal: RTP announces hosts to Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=30 January 2012|publisher=oikotimes.com|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> The winner was determined by a combination of the votes from 20 regional juries (50%) and televoting (50%).<ref name=\"Portugal2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/12/09/open-call-to-singers-starts-today/|title=Portugal: Open call to singers starts today|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=9 December 2011|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201175011/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/12/09/open-call-to-singers-starts-today/|archivedate=1 February 2012|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"9\" |Final \u2013 10 March 2012\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Draw\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Artist\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Song\n! colspan=\"2\" |Jury\n! colspan=\"2\" |Televote\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Total\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Place\n|-\n!Votes\n!Points\n!Percentage\n!Points\n|- \n|1\n| align=\"left\" |Ricardo Soler\n| align=\"left\" |\"Gratia plena\"\n|109\n|5\n|13.38%\n|8\n|13\n|4\n|- \n|2\n| align=\"left\" |Pedro Macedo\n| align=\"left\" |\"Outono em forma de gente\"\n|38\n|0\n|6.23%\n|5\n|5\n|8\n|- \n|3\n| align=\"left\" |T\u00f3 Martins\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amanh\u00e3 come\u00e7a o meu futuro\"\n|88\n|4\n|1.62%\n|0\n|4\n|11\n|-\n|4\n| align=\"left\" |Gerson Santos\n| align=\"left\" |\"Redescobrir Portugal\"\n|43\n|1\n|1.90%\n|0\n|1\n|12\n|- \n|5\n| align=\"left\" |Joana Leite\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor \u00e9 maior que a vida\"\n|78\n|3\n|3.55%\n|2\n|5\n|8\n|-\n|6\n| align=\"left\" |Pamela Salvado\n| align=\"left\" |\"Fica a saudade\"\n|123\n|8\n|5.41%\n|4\n|12\n|5\n|- \n|7\n| align=\"left\" |C\u00famplices\n| align=\"left\" |\"Ser\u00e1 o que ser\u00e1\"\n|151\n|10\n|7.36%\n|6\n|16\n|2\n|-\n|8\n| align=\"left\" |Arm\u00e9nio Pimenta\n| align=\"left\" |\"Um poema na bagagem\"\n|69\n|2\n|4.60%\n|3\n|5\n|8\n|-\n|9\n| align=\"left\" |Carlos Costa\n| align=\"left\" |\"Queres que eu dance?\"\n|30\n|0\n|14.66%\n|10\n|10\n|6\n|-\n|10\n| align=\"left\" |V\u00e2nia Os\u00f3rio\n| align=\"left\" |\"O mundo passa\"\n|115\n|6\n|2.77%\n|1\n|7\n|7\n|- \n|11\n| align=\"left\" |Rui Andrade\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor a preto e branco\"\n|119\n|7\n|13.17%\n|7\n|14\n|3\n|- bgcolor=\"gold\"\n|'''12'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''[[Filipa Sousa]]'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''\"Vida minha\"'''\n|'''197'''\n|'''12'''\n|'''25.28%'''\n|'''12'''\n|'''24'''\n|'''1'''\n|- \n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center;font-size:85%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"23\" |Detailed Regional Jury Votes\n|-\n!Draw\n!Song\n!<small>[[Aveiro, Portugal|Aveiro]]</small>\n!<small>[[Beja, Portugal|Beja]]</small>\n!<small>[[Braga]]</small>\n!<small>[[Bragan\u00e7a, Portugal|Bragan\u00e7a]]</small>\n!<small>[[Castelo Branco, Portugal|Castelo]]</small><br><small>[[Castelo Branco, Portugal|Branco]]</small>\n!<small>[[Coimbra]]</small>\n!<small>[[\u00c9vora]]</small>\n!<small>[[Faro, Portugal|Faro]]</small>\n!<small>[[Madeira]]</small>\n!<small>[[Guarda, Portugal|Guarda]]</small>\n!<small>[[Leiria]]</small>\n!<small>[[Lisbon]]</small>\n!<small>[[Azores|A\u00e7ores]]</small>\n!<small>[[Portalegre District|Portalegre]]</small>\n!<small>[[Porto]]</small>\n!<small>[[Santar\u00e9m, Portugal|Santar\u00e9m]]</small>\n!<small>[[Set\u00fabal]]</small>\n!<small>[[Viana do Castelo|Viana]]</small><br><small>[[Viana do Castelo|do Castelo]]</small>\n!<small>[[Vila Real|Vila]]</small><br><small>[[Vila Real|Real]]</small>\n!<small>[[Viseu]]</small>\n!Total\n|-\n|1\n| align=\"left\" |\"Gratia plena\"\n|\n|7\n|7\n|8\n|10\n|8\n|\n|2\n|\n|4\n|7\n|'''12'''\n|5\n|10\n|2\n|7\n|'''12'''\n|5\n|\n|3\n|109\n|-\n|2\n| align=\"left\" | \"Outono em forma de gente\" ||  || ||  || 1 || 7\n|\n|\n| 7\n|1\n|2\n|2\n|\n|\n|3\n|\n|2\n|2\n|2\n|5\n|4|| 38\n|-\n|3\n| align=\"left\" | \"Amanh\u00e3 come\u00e7a o meu futuro\" || 3 || 2 || 2 || 2 || 5\n|7\n|8\n| 10\n|4\n|5\n|\n|5\n|4\n|\n|4\n|10\n|\n|6\n|1\n|10|| 88\n|-\n|4\n| align=\"left\" | \"Redescobrir Portugal\" || 1 || 8 ||  ||  || 3\n|5\n|3\n| \n|2\n|3\n|\n|1\n|2\n|1\n|1\n|1\n|6\n|3\n|3\n| || 43\n|-\n|5\n| align=\"left\" | \"Amor \u00e9 maior que a vida\" || 5 || 3 || 3 || 7 || 1\n|1\n|10\n| 6\n|7\n|\n|6\n|\n|3\n|4\n|5\n|8\n|4\n|1\n|2\n|2|| 78\n|-\n|6\n| align=\"left\" | \"Fica a saudade\" || 8 || 4 || 10 || 5 || 8\n|6\n|7\n| 1\n|\n|7\n|3\n|8\n|7\n|5\n|8\n|'''12'''\n|5\n|7\n|7\n|5|| 123\n|-\n|7\n| align=\"left\" | \"Ser\u00e1 o que ser\u00e1\" || 10 || 10 || 6 || 10 || \n|10\n|6\n| 4\n|10\n|10\n|10\n|10\n|'''12'''\n|6\n|10\n|6\n|3\n|4\n|6\n|8|| 151\n|-\n|8\n| align=\"left\" | \"Um poema na bagagem\" || 4 || 1 ||4||3|| 6\n|2\n|4\n|5\n|6\n|\n|1\n|4\n|1\n|7\n|\n|4\n|\n|8\n|8\n|1|| 69\n|-\n|9\n| align=\"left\" | \"Queres que eu dance?\" || 2 ||  || 1 ||  || \n|3\n|1\n| 8\n|3\n|1\n|5\n|2\n|\n|\n|3\n|\n|1\n|\n|\n| || 30\n|-\n|10\n| align=\"left\" | \"O mundo passa\" ||7|| 5 || 8 || 4 ||'''12'''\n|\n|5\n| 3\n|8\n|8\n|8\n|6\n|8\n|8\n|7\n|\n|7\n|\n|4\n|7|| 115\n|-\n|11\n| align=\"left\" | \"Amor a preto e branco\" || 6 || 6 || 5 || 6 ||2\n|2\n|'''12'''\n| \n|'''12'''\n|6\n|4\n|3\n|6\n|2\n|6\n|3\n|10\n|10\n|10\n|6|| 119\n|-\n|12\n| align=\"left\" | \"Vida minha\" ||'''12'''||'''12'''||'''12'''||'''12'''|| 4\n|'''12'''\n|2\n|'''12'''\n|5\n|'''12'''\n|'''12'''\n|7\n|10\n|'''12'''\n|'''12'''\n|5\n|8\n|'''12'''\n|'''12'''\n|'''12'''|| 197\n|}\n==At Eurovision==\nPortugal competed 6th in the second semi-final on 24 May.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hondal|first=Victor|title=Insignia exchange and semifinal allocation draw.|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/18162|publisher=EscToday.com}}</ref> After the voting, Filipa Sousa finished in 13th position with 39 points, which meant that for the second year in a row Portugal did not qualify for the final.\n\n===Points awarded by Portugal<ref>[[Eurovision Song Contest 2012]]</ref>===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Semi-final 2====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"gold\"|'''12 points'''||{{Esc|EST}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"silver\"|'''10 points'''||{{Esc|SWE}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"#CC9966\"|'''8 points'''||{{Esc|SRB}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''7 points'''||{{Esc|LIT}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''6 points'''||{{Esc|BUL}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''5 points'''||{{Esc|BIH}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''4 points'''||{{Esc|SVK}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''3 points'''||{{Esc|NOR}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''2 points'''||{{Esc|UKR}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''1 point'''||{{Esc|GEO}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Final====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"gold\"|'''12 points'''||{{Esc|ESP}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"silver\"|'''10 points'''||{{Esc|GER}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"#CC9966\"|'''8 points'''||{{Esc|RUS}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''7 points'''||{{Esc|EST}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''6 points'''||{{Esc|MDA}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''5 points'''||{{Esc|SRB}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''4 points'''||{{Esc|ROM}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''3 points'''||{{Esc|SWE}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''2 points'''||{{Esc|ITA}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''1 point'''||{{Esc|UKR}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Jury points awarded by Portugal===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Semi-final 2====\nJury points awarded in second semi-final:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=20%|'''12 points'''||{{Esc|Estonia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''10 points'''||{{Esc|Serbia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''8 points'''||{{Esc|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''7 points'''||{{Esc|Slovakia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''6 points'''||{{Esc|Sweden}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''5 points'''||{{Esc|Georgia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''4 points'''||{{Esc|Croatia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''3 points'''||{{Esc|Malta}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''2 points'''||{{Esc|Belarus}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''1 point'''||{{Esc|Slovenia}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Final====\nJury points awarded in the final:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=20%|'''12 points'''||{{Esc|Spain}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''10 points'''||{{Esc|Germany}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''8 points'''||{{Esc|Estonia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''7 points'''||{{Esc|Serbia}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''6 points'''||{{Esc|Italy}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''5 points'''||{{Esc|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''4 points'''||{{Esc|France}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''3 points'''||{{Esc|Albania}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''2 points'''||{{Esc|Iceland}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''1 point'''||{{Esc|Russia}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+Points awarded to Portugal (semi-final 2)\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|FRA}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|NED}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|NOR}}\n*{{esc|SVK}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|BIH}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|CRO}}\n*{{esc|GER}}\n*{{esc|SLO}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{esc|LIT}}\n*{{esc|TUR}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|pt}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20120122001345/http://ww1.rtp.pt/icmblogs/rtp/comunicacao/?k=Regulamento-Festival-da-Cancao-2012---RTP.rtp&post=37042 Competition rules] ''[[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]''\n\n{{Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2012}}\n\n[[Category:Countries in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012]]\n[[Category:Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\n[[Category:2012 in Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox song contest national year \n| Year                  = 2012\n| Country                = Portugal\n| Preselection           = Festival Da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012\n| Preselection date      = 10 March 2012\n| Entrant                = [[Filipa Sousa]]\n| Song                   = [[Vida minha]]\n| SF result              = ''Failed to qualify'' (13th, 39 points)\n| Prev                   = 2011\n| Next                   = 2014\n}}\n'''Portugal''' participated in the '''Eurovision Song Contest 2012''' in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]]. The Portuguese entry was selected through Festival Da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012,  a national final organised by the Portuguese broadcaster [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]. [[Filipa Sousa]] represented Portugal with the song \"[[Vida minha]]\", which failed to qualify from the second semi-final, achieving 13th place with 39 points.<ref name=semi2results>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 2012 Semi-Final (2)|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=1583#Scoreboard|work=Eurovision.tv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Victor M.|last=Escuerdo|title=Filipa Sousa for Portugal in Baku|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=48813&_t=filipa_sousa_for_portugal_in_baku|work=Eurovision.tv|date=11 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nPortugal was considered to withdraw, because of the economic crisis in the country, but on 30 November 2011, RTP confirmed its participation in the Eurovision Song Contest 2012 in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]].<ref name=\"Portugal1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/11/25/portugal-decides-on-march-10/|title=Portugal decides on March 10th|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=25 November 2011|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129032047/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/11/25/portugal-decides-on-march-10/|archivedate=29 November 2011|accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Before Eurovision ==\n\n=== Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012 ===\n''Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o 2012'' was the 48th edition of [[Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o]], the music competition that selects Portugal's entries for the Eurovision Song Contest.\n\n==== Competing entries ====\nArtists were able to submit their applications through the RTP official website before 31 December 2011. Applicants then advanced to the auditions that were held in [[Lisbon]] (5 and 6 January 2012) and [[Oporto]] (10 and 11 January 2012), where they had to sing in Portuguese or in a foreign language (e.g. English). An exception was made for applications from established artists, which they can directly send in their songs to RTP without having to go through the auditions. RTS received more than 400 applications, and a jury chose 12 candidates and 5 back-ups to compete in the national final, which were revealed on 13 January 2012.<ref name=\"Portugal3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/02/rtp-receives-more-than-400-applications/|title=RTP receives more than 400 applications|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=2 January 2012|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112052527/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/02/rtp-receives-more-than-400-applications/|archivedate=12 January 2012|accessdate=2 January 2012}}</ref> Three of the final twelve artists: Carlos Costa, Ricardo Soler and Rui Andrade didn't go through the auditions, using instead their recognition as moderate established artists. Soler competed in the [[Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2008|2008]] edition of Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o, finishing fourth, while Andrade finished third in the [[Portugal in the Eurovision Song Contest 2011|2011]] edition.<ref name=\"Portugal4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/13/rtp-announces-the-national-finalists//|title=Portugal: RTP announces 2012 national finalists|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=13 January 2012|publisher=oikotimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nRTP then directly invited six composers from various musical styles to compose songs for the selected artists. Composers and authors will create new songs specially for the 12 candidates, in order to suit their vocal skills. The songs must be no longer than three minutes, and had to be performed in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]. Two music producers were also invited by RTP to work in coordination with the composers in produce the 12 entries.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! Artist\n! Song\n! Lyrics (l) / Music (m)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Arm\u00e9nio Pimenta\n| align=\"left\" |\"Um poema na bagagem\"\n| align=\"left\" |Menito Ramos (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Carlos Costa\n| align=\"left\" |\"Queres que eu dance?\"\n| align=\"left\" |Jo\u00e3o S\u00f3 (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |C\u00famplices\n| align=\"left\" |\"Ser\u00e1 o que ser\u00e1\"\n| align=\"left\" |Jony Galv\u00e3o, Rui Reis (m&l)\n|- bgcolor=\"gold\"\n| align=\"left\" |'''[[Filipa Sousa]]'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''\"[[Vida minha]]\"'''\n| align=\"left\" |'''[[Andrej Babi\u0107]] (m), Carlos Coelho (l)'''\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Gerson Santos\n| align=\"left\" |\"Redescobrir Portugal\"\n| align=\"left\" |T\u00f3 Z\u00e9 (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Joana Leite\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor \u00e9 maior que a vida\"\n| align=\"left\" |Tiago Dias (m), Marisa Liz(l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Pamela Salvado\n| align=\"left\" |\"Fica a saudade\"\n| align=\"left\" |[[Miguel Gameiro]] (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Pedro Macedo\n| align=\"left\" |\"Outono em forma de gente\"\n| align=\"left\" |Pedro Marques (m&l), [[Daniela Varela]] (m&l), Jaime Oliveira  (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Ricardo Soler\n| align=\"left\" |\"Gratia plena\"\n| align=\"left\" |Nuno Feist (m), Nuno Silva (l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |Rui Andrade\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amor a preto e branco\"\n| align=\"left\" |Miguel Majer (m&l), In\u00eas Vaz (l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |T\u00f3 Martins\n| align=\"left\" |\"Amanh\u00e3 come\u00e7a o meu futuro\"\n| align=\"left\" |Toz\u00e9 Brito (m&l)\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |V\u00e2nia Os\u00f3rio\n| align=\"left\" |\"O mundo passa\"\n| align=\"left\" |Armando Teixeira (m&l)\n|- \n|}\n==== Final ====\nThe final was held on 10 March 2012, hosted by [[S\u00edlvia Alberto]] and Pedro Granger.<ref name=\"Portugal5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2012/01/30/rtp-annouces-hosts-to-festival-da-cancao///|title=Portugal: RTP announces hosts to Festival da Can\u00e7\u00e3o|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=30 January 2012|publisher=oikotimes.com|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> The winner was determined by a combination of the votes from 20 regional juries (50%) and televoting (50%).<ref name=\"Portugal2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/12/09/open-call-to-singers-starts-today/|title=Portugal: Open call to singers starts today|last=Costa|first=Nelson|date=9 December 2011|publisher=OIKOTIMES.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201175011/http://www.oikotimes.com/eurovision/2011/12/09/open-call-to-singers-starts-today/|archivedate=1 February 2012|accessdate=9 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto; text-align:center\"\n! colspan=\"9\" |Final \u2013 10 March 2012\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Draw\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Artist\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Song\n! colspan=\"2\" |Jury\n! colspan=\"2\" |Televote\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Total\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Place\n|-\n!Votes\n!Points\n!Percentage\n!Points\n|- \n|1\n| align=\"left\" |Ricardo Soler\n| align=\"left\" |\"Gratia plena\"\n|109\n|5\n|13.38%\n|8\n|13\n|4\n|- \n|2\n| align=\"left\"